late well-versed korean food: joomak melbourne melbourne, australia — hard argue barbecue fried chicken. two foods snaked way australian restaurant zeitgeist like recent years, edible americana become ubiquitous here. two giants southern cookery also culinary emissaries korean culture. ambassadors go, can’t get much charming irresistible sizzling meats crispy chicken served plenty beer.there much korean food, however, greasy darlings, places melbourne explore vast deliciousness. get decent bibimbap there, kimchi shows cafe menus almost often dukkah days. much harder find bubbling caldrons jjigae, turned blazing scarlet kimchi chiles, dotted pork bulbous clouds soon tofu.in book, stews life’s elemental necessary dishes. sure, barbecue fried chicken make fantastic companions beer rice-based liquors, korean cuisine wicked brilliance comes drunk-food seen melbourne. found joomak.it easy feat: joomak, opened 2010, basement personality-less swanston street office building melbourne’s central business district, street signage indicating right location. enter building feeling wholly unsure descending flight stairs lead heavy wooden door. though name restaurant staircase, note basement door explains business cash-only, step room entirely sure found place. help map apps phone put joomak nearby alley, encountered bewildered would-be customers searching entrance dumpsters. use street address, name restaurant.who cramming long, low room, booths tucked nooks along sides? mainly young people speaking korean. blended sochu fruit slushies (the pineapple version best) pitchers, unfiltered rice wine tap, served metal teakettles drunk shallow metal bowls. food goes drinking: corn kernels heaped pile smothered melted cheese; egg rolls stuffed cheese fish roe; yes, spicy pan-fried chicken.i came jjigae, listed english joomak’s menu “kimchi pork soup tofu,” presumably word “jjigae” yet make lexicon non-korean-speaking australian. came bubbling black caldron, satiated lust piquant, porky comfort. certainly better versions. joomak’s kimchi pancake could hang best them, perfectly greasy crisped crust giving way slightly creamy interior, proficient soaking booze street pizza. (the seafood pancake pretty fine, too.) spicy chicken gizzards, sizzling platter, lose bouncy magic cool rubbery nubs. first bites fantastic.there common theory los angeles’s giant korean population koreatown neighborhood strong influence korean food culture worldwide. america high-quality beef, one result beef-based dishes. see joomak “l.a.-style short ribs,” cut thin cooked crispy, flesh sweet soy garlic.australia subtle influences, too. “school prawns,” common bar snack fried shrimp, much different joomak number melbourne pubs, eaten head-on served aioli. dish kabana sausage stir-fried vegetables ultimate multicultural mash-up — korean take australian version polish sausage.a helpful hint: call ahead make booking. joomak one melbourne’s rare extremely-late-night licenses, likely taking advantage late hours decide wander without warning. efficient, harried staff take name quote two-to-three-hour wait table. nowhere restaurant wait. go drink somewhere else check back phone intermittently. persistence pays off.in seoul, los angeles, youth culture food culture inextricably intertwined, much like fashion tokyo hip-hop atlanta. ancient methods ingredients still respected, force drives creativity excitement revenue restaurant industry food-obsessed millennials. midnight friday nights, swanston street packed young people korean, vietnamese chinese descent, energy foretells melbourne bound become increasingly influenced asian youth culture.through door stairs, joomak window culture late-night, sochu-soaked vibrancy.do suggestion besha rodell? new york times’s australia bureau would love hear you: nytaustralia@nytimes.com join discussion nyt australia facebook group. read australia fare column here.follow nyt food facebook, instagram, twitter pinterest. get regular updates nyt cooking, re