sydney ‘war zone’ became center vietnamese resolve sydney, australia — generation ago, people arriving train cabramatta, western sydney, would exit station find bustling open-air heroin market gangs gunfights turf.“honest god, war zone,” said detective superintendent scott cook, commander new south wales organized crime squad, began policing career cabramatta 1989. “we’d walk street get lunch arrest two people.”now, lunch still draw, though arrests wane. mix aggressive policing, government intervention hard work residents, cabramatta undergone stark transformation lively area renowned destination sydney’s best vietnamese food.the area’s reputation crime arose 1970s, surging drug trade coincided arrival thousands vietnamese migrants refugees. among first nonwhite migrants australia complete abolition white australia policy 1973, many newcomers risked lives harrowing boat trips settling vietnam war.as australia’s offshore detention policy condemned human rights groups, cabramatta shows challenges refugee communities face, also evolve.today signs old cabramatta. busiest thoroughfare, john street, recently opened canary-yellow bubble tea shop sits near cellphone store, joining hip burger joint array sugar-cane juice stalls, fabric markets ethnic grocery stores.“cabramatta always good place me,” said bubble tea shop’s owner, quynh nguyen, 31, came sydney teenager ho chi minh city. “i feel homey here.”a mix fresh ambition familiar come define diverse neighborhood, less 10 percent population traces ancestry australia england. visible places like usual cafe, modern coffee shop near john street baristas denim pull shots background lush plants white tiles.corey nguyen, 28, grew australia owns usual partner, jenny ngo, said wanted introduce cabramatta, dominated traditional cafes selling vietnamese-style coffee, artisanal cafe culture.“for us it’s never competition,” said. “they thing, ours. wish best.”it’s good thing, said andrew nguyen, 24, waited friend coffee traditional vietnamese lunch. “all asian fixes here,” said. “it’s home us.”for many cabramatta’s first vietnamese residents, felt like anything but.before arrival, population mostly working-class australians european migrants. german-austrian society center near train station one remaining signs past.during ’70s, primarily american servicemen brought heroin sydney southeast asia, said andrew jakubowicz, professor sociology university technology sydney. cabramatta, links italian criminal groups new connection southeast asia, would soon become distribution point rest city.for vietnamese, harboring lingering trauma war, lack established asian community cabramatta made “a fairly desperate time,” professor jakubowicz said. “there history structure available respond to, australia still racist.”one former refugees, hue kim, 75, spends weekends selling kaffir lime leaves, rosemary herbs sidewalk feet ms. nguyen’s bubble tea shop.she remembers attending first english class shortly arriving, pregnant, sydney 37 years ago. teachers, said, noticed shirt stained milk. “they told nurse newborn coming back,” said vietnamese. “so didn’t go back.”many vietnamese children came time unaccompanied. others left devices parents worked long hours. isolated culturally economically, young vietnamese arrivals banded together, tapping drug trade preying members community.tony hoang, 35, pastor spent teenage years dealing heroin part gang, recalled time marked instability, anger need belong. “it attractive part group loved other,” said.the violence took shocking turn 1994 assassination john newman, represented cabramatta state parliament. rival local politician immigrated vietnam later convicted crime.it australia’s first political assassination, one would feed notions wave ethnic migrant violence cabramatta.frustration area’s lawless reputation eventually prompted parliamentary inquiry. 2001 report led creation drug treatment intervention programs hiring police officers wider powers tackle drug crimes. today, crime levels compare parts metropolitan sydney.not cabramatta’s problems solved. housing prices, like elsewhere sydney, risen millions dollars.and new wave migrants, including refugees syria middle east, raising kinds tensions confronted vietnamese migrants 1970s.according 2016 census, vietnamese still predominant ethnic group cabramatta, making 33 percent roughly 22,000 residents. chinese make 24 percent, cambodians account 8 percent. least 40 ethnic groups also represented.frank carbone, mayor fairfield city, western sydney district surrounding cabramatta, said 7,000 new refugees resettled region since january 2016, federal government provided financial support.today, though, children initial wave vietnamese migrants seeing return parents’ persistence creating legacy.on quieter stretch john street, patrons lined outside pho tau bay, popular restaurant. inside, chi giang, 36, placid man glasses, worked register waiters ferried bowls steaming broth.born indonesian refugee camp vietnamese parents waiting australian visas, mr. giang manages restaurant, mother began kitchen home 1980. closely guarded beef noodle soup recipe often tops critics’ lists best vietnamese food sydney, profits restaurant enough sustain mr. giang’s entire extended family.“over years, i’ve seen kids coming babies,” mr. giang said, gesturing young family nearby table. “and years later, they’re taller me, they’re still coming beef noodle soup.”
‘the good doctor,’ anti-antihero title abc’s “the good doctor” simple complicated. mostly, show exactly sounds like: hospital melodrama, whiz-bang medical science, dash intra-staff romance shameless sentimentality. it’s competent good, it’s well-versed workings human tear duct.what makes distinctive — possibly made it, debut season, one most-watched shows television — way interrogates word “good.” it, show asks, simply effective?“the good doctor” that, counterintuitively, protagonist whose inability connect emotionally one defining features. dr. shaun murphy (freddie highmore), new surgeon prestigious hospital san jose, calif., autism savant syndrome.earnest distant, shaun often needs simple responses explained him, like parents would sad hear son going lose leg amputation save life.he’s also brilliant surgeon, able make intuitive leaps elude others. (in mold difficult-genius dramas like “sherlock,” “the good doctor” visualizes insights 3-d graphics, like diagram liver explodes segments explain function key vein.) still, skeptical co-workers, like dr. neil melendez (nicholas gonzalez), see liability.“the good doctor” sharp enough leave open possibility might sometimes point. shaun’s inability read cues alienate patients. he’s cogitating diagnosis, goes blank, like computer app spinning-wheel mode, show suspends tension long enough you, like colleagues, wonder something’s gone wrong.the conceit “the good doctor” condition limits shaun’s human interactions inseparable gift. can’t speak accuracy representation autism — neither doctor, play one tv — shaun’s emotional challenge show’s emotional engine.shaun may understand human relations well enough know that, say, shouldn’t wake apartment superintendent midnight. mr. highmore (“bates motel”) makes appealing eager, unintentionally comic candor. (his version reassuring diagnosis: “it’s definitely flesh-eating bacteria!”) root advocate, dr. aaron glassman (richard schiff).“the good doctor” adapted south korean series david shore, creator “house,” different sort difficult protagonist. dr. gregory house (hugh laurie) crusty, arrogant physician sharp-elbowed spirit post-9/11 aughts, figures jack bauer “24” simon cowell “american idol” popularized idea nice guys don’t get job done.on “house,” doctor’s misanthropy much strength liability — suspicion (“everybody lies”) lack sentiment led ingenious diagnoses.in “good doctor” pilot, shaun asks something dismissive superior could aimed tv predecessor. “you’re arrogant,” says. “do think helps good surgeon? hurt person? worth it?”on page, sounds sanctimonious angry, shaun asks curiosity. that’s way. he’s cuddly warm, he’s guileless well intentioned — anti-antihero version gregory house. shaun fellow young doctors learning art dealing frightened patients, getting feel proper dosage tact, honesty, sympathy willingness bend rules.while may different ways good express caring, “the good doctor” suggests, something worth aspiring — idea may especially appeal viewers experienced health care scary, impersonal alienating.elsewhere, “the good doctor” creates emotional investment old-fashioned way: stabbing hypodermic needle straight heart.the manipulative incidental music abundant, heart-wrenching scenarios. bus carrying wedding party crashes one episode; another, meet young boy cancer charming wise that, watched one medical drama life, know he’s long world.we also get series bludgeoningly woeful flashbacks shaun’s childhood — father beats him, brother dies, pet rabbit dies — show thankfully dialed back lately. even mr. schiff, known playing acerbic characters like toby ziegler “the west wing,” cast avuncular guardian teddy bear.but mr. schiff convincing role, mr. highmore striking his. “the good doctor” hardly reinvented syrupy, tear-jerking medical drama. found new way complicate genre’s oldest idea: human connection best medicine.
kenneth macmillan’s school ballet sex, neurosis grit london — 25 years since choreographer kenneth macmillan fatal heart attack backstage royal opera house performance “mayerling,” ballet sex, drugs, madness death. long night, told wife “might another 10 15 years” life successful ballets — “romeo juliet,” “manon,” “mayerling.” chronically anxious self-doubting, macmillan far modest hopes.today, ballets britain’s best-known dance exports, plentiful major ballet company repertories worldwide (25 companies currently perform “manon”), still probably successful 20th-century examples story ballet genre.in adaptations literature history, perpetuated ballet’s tradition lavish spectacle set past age. also effectively reinvented 19th-century narrative ballet audience ready tales passion, drama violence rather involving myths, swans chivalry. — like jerome robbins antony tudor united states — bringer neurosis, psychological drama real-life grit rarefied world ballet.“kenneth macmillan: national celebration,” took place oct. 16 nov. 1 royal opera house, commemorated 25th anniversary choreographer’s death 62. refreshingly, feature blockbuster ballets. instead offered eight one-acts — many seldom staged — chance think macmillan’s reputation legacy away omnipresent long narrative works.the pieces — ranging “baiser de la fée” (1960) “the judas tree,” created months death — performed britain’s five major ballet companies: royal ballet, english national ballet, scottish ballet, birmingham royal ballet northern ballet. (the small yorke dance project also came party, intriguing revival almost unknown 1988 chamber piece, “sea troubles,” inspired shakespeare’s “hamlet.”) collaboration, idea kevin o’hare, director royal ballet, unusual. several companies seldom come london, almost never share stage audience.macmillan, desire rend decorous veil ballet, often seen polar opposite major 20th-century british choreographer, frederick ashton, whose refined, lyrical witty pieces (“la fille mal gardée,” “symphonic variations,” “sylvia”) came define pre-macmillan era british classical dance.“kenneth macmillan dark genius british ballet — destroyer, listen some,” critic ismene brown wrote article celebration spectator magazine.but wasn’t macmillan’s subject matter, could include rape (“the invitation”), incest (“my brother, sisters”) sexual sadism (“mayerling”), bothered critics. also use ballet technique suggest states extreme emotion erotic desire. 1981, piece royal ballet’s 50th-birthday season metropolitan opera house new york, arlene croce wrote danger “pearly classicism” ashtonian style “is new religiose preoccupation human body contortions pronounced macmillan’s ballets.”looking ballets now, physical demands look tame compared athletic requirements many current ballet choreographers. subject matter sometimes brutal, choreographic content mostly firmly classical, though often extended new expressive terrain.in macmillan’s 1965 masterwork, “song earth,” beautifully danced celebration english national ballet, gestures imagery idiosyncratic strange, sometimes alluding chinese t’ang poems used (in german translation) mahler score. women delicately mime picking flowers, turned upside text, sung onstage tenor mezzo-soprano, alludes pavilion reflected water. details vignettes part austere classicism, rather new choreographic language, slowly building evoke poetic specific world.more surprising, less well-known, “concerto,” first work macmillan made took new job artistic director deutsche oper ballet berlin 1966. (he returned england 1969 take directorship royal ballet.)“concerto,” danced celebration birmingham royal ballet, bright, pure exercise ballet classicism, set shostakovich’s piano concerto no. 2, and, among things, it’s brilliant demonstration macmillan’s musicality, aspect work previously considered. music’s jazziness echoed hip-tilted inflections first third sections, marching rhythms reflected, without emphasis, phalanxes moving bodies might refer armies militaristic drill corps de ballet.but it’s second movement, adagio, affecting. here, woman holds man, executing smooth, flowing sequence arcing bends languorous stretches. (macmillan said inspired watching lynn seymour, longtime muse, warm barre.) it’s particularly interesting light current thoughts conventionality male-female partnering ballet; moment man cast nothing support — yet macmillan creates something poetic ambiguous matter-of-fact relationship: thinking eyes meet end?other macmillan pieces feel less important interesting; 1974 “elite syncopations” (performed mix principals different companies) set music scott joplin ragtime composers, insistent perkiness slightly hammy jokes pall, even though choreographically challenging smoothly constructed. “gloria” (well danced northern ballet), created 1980 set poulenc, moving slightly dated feel (this partly costume problem), ballet vocabulary makes much physical tension soaring uplift grounded, earthbound despair.and perhaps difficult ballet macmillan oeuvre, “the judas tree.” set construction site london docklands, features single woman 12 male laborers. woman, seductress victim, raped men, one murdered another commits suicide. biblical allusions jesus, mary, judas perhaps another disciple, story line muddled hard interpret. (who judas, kept wondering.) choreography, however, excellent: inventive, expressionistic, surprising, emotionally compelling. can’t look; can’t look away.it’s impossible ballet like, though, light harvey weinstein revelations repercussions, hard questions become even harder. aesthetic beauty ballet tame make palatable violence see onstage? show us aspects human behavior shy away from, especially opera house? judge subject matter art, different things?these questions ways haunted macmillan’s work early on. 25th anniversary celebration made strong case position major 20th-century artist without providing neat answers.
