secret long life? ‘it’s good work lot’ hard work key longevity, says bella pevzner, 89.“i worked hard life,” said. “that’s stay long. it’s good work lot.”a heart operation 2002 halted irrepressible work ethic. “i retired age 74,” mrs. pevzner said recently. “if operation, maybe i’d work more. workaholic. tell you?”that dogged determination keep going rooted formative years. teenager, fled home country belarus 1941 nazis invaded it.her parents sister escaped, many relatives, among mrs. pevzner’s grandparents younger sister, slaughtered.after harrowing 300-mile journey, family found sanctuary kazakhstan. food resources scarce years. recalled walking barefoot snow. father, tailor, fashioned clothing flour sacks family.“we stayed there,” mrs. pevzner said. “it hard life.”after war, family settled ukraine, lived small basement apartment. slept iron beds, using rags mattress padding. years, mrs. pevzner one set garments: underwear, slippers cherry-colored dress white dots.“i washed every day, went work every day clothes,” said.mrs. pevzner worked bookkeeper help support household. 1953, matchmaker introduced man would marry. year later, son born.shortly mother died, mrs. pevzner, 50, immigrated united states husband son. know word english, wasted time learning it.“it hard learn dictionary, learned speaking,” mrs. pevzner said. “in brooklyn, walked streets, jewish people met talked yiddish, told them: ‘no, language. never forget. need speak english. speak english!’ insistent.”mrs. pevzner continued work 70s various employers, bookkeeper accountant, credits exercising mind keeping sharp. recalled one job bakery boss threatened fire use calculator compute discounts offered regular customers.“i figured everything head,” mrs. pevzner said. “my head good. it’s still bad.”today, mrs. pevzner says feels lucky 63-year-old son lives apartment across street home bensonhurst, brooklyn.her husband died liver cancer 2011, age taken toll health. diabetes, sleep apnea, hypertension, gout, respiratory illness, thyroid problems retinal disease.“i lot sickness, better tell want don’t have,” mrs. pevzner said. “it’s hard, hard, manage it. try best.”in 2014, jewish association serving aging, beneficiary agency uja-federation new york, began delivering mrs. pevzner kosher meals. uja-federation new york one eight organizations supported new york times neediest cases fund.mrs. pevzner receives $1,232 month social security income. april, association used $75 fund mrs. pevzner could buy fruit bake dishes passover meal. money also went toward buying special eye drops treat retinal disease. additional $46 used august provide mrs. pevzner shower bench.retirement allowed discover new interests. took painting age 80 visit center older adults. much art features animals landscapes, many creations hang frames walls. paintings remain unfinished; failing eyesight delayed completion.mrs. pevzner says expects continue thriving despite many maladies. father lived 97, determined live least 100. still much done, explained.“i don’t lose hope,” mrs. pevzner said. “i pictures finished, need finish.”
