gay husband, dire diagnosis best-laid plans old yiddish proverb goes: man plans god laughs.and man, plan. careers require much planning career medicine. process enough encompass life one person; add another mix, planning becomes all-consuming.jarrett met pre-med freshmen chemistry lab became fast friends, laughing flame bunsen burner set experiments. soon inseparable, playing endless games dr. mario nintendo study sessions. sometimes, night fraternity hazing, would come dorm room profess love me. initially laughed off, reminding best friend. spring freshman year, relationship changed. felt beshert — meant be. driven love mutual goals, started planning.we managed get residency programs city moved new york chicago, two newly crowned m.d.’s flush excitement perfectly executed wedding sent us off.but working combined 160 hours per week tough marriage. cheerful, thoughtful husband becoming increasingly moody distant. confronted him: affair? no! love anymore? no. gay? silence.“i think might be,” said.with words, everything changed. stayed nights end, talking circles. withdrew world, retreating closet along him. “we love other, fix this,” told ourselves. eventually became clear “fixable” problem. gradually confided family friends, putting aside reluctance “out” him; jarrett came same, finally accepting long-hidden part himself. moved finished latter half residencies newly single, plunging world online dating, market thirtysomething men.i learned live without him. “matched” again, planned move philadelphia — new start.the next hiccup plans cough. first, mostly near-daily four-mile run, soon constant. time, reading “when breath becomes air” dr. paul kalanithi, neurosurgery resident learned stage iv lung cancer age 36. fleeting moment panic, shared fear co-resident reading book. confessed similar thoughts, reassured — course neither us lung cancer. winter; worked hospital; everyone coughing.i still wearing hospital scrubs went get chest x-ray.maybe that’s technician spoke unusually direct way: “i’m radiologist, definitely something there.”despite best plans “start over” divorce, jarrett ended philadelphia fellowships. seen since move, eyes met across sweaty room spin studio. resolutely decided interact necessary.it seemed necessary. knew people new city. suddenly seemed beshert ex lived worked right next door. jarrett first person called doctor’s office was, immediately side resume abandoned duties best friend.i spent following days hospital, family beside me, balancing wobbly tightrope separated doctor patient. medical team would come relay information complicated jargon often familiar lay english. found translating everything back terrified parents, patients trying soften blow bad news.“right inferior mediastinal mass encasing occluding right inferior pulmonary vein” became “i something looks like tumor middle chest.” “favored represent lymphoma” became, “i probably type blood cancer, get that.” “other unusual primary lung malignancies occur patient age, considered much less likely” became “don’t worry, don’t lung cancer.”the morning oncologist came hospital room told lung cancer, laughing parents. it’s expecting good news, wasn’t. unprepared hear “lung cancer” hear jarrett say “i’m gay.”i felt begin tip tightrope tried grab back on, terrified begin long descent toward “patient” side. wavered, could hear mother background trying assure “we’d get it.” oncologist, voice cracking, explained parents plain english cancers curable. mine stage iv.i still tried translate, time could barely get words out. “that means going live long life.”as physician, trained observant, pick subtle clues. sometimes think determined stick plan neglected see right front me. consider many men like flowers mean gay, many 32-year-olds get cough winter lung cancer.i living cancer year. treatment has, times, left feeling sicker could ever imagined. felt deeply angry, profoundly sad all-around terrified.but first time, also learning enjoy instead focusing later. might never see finish line fellowship graduation, still doctor; lucky enough learning every day still make patients’ lives better. years education training allowed build supportive community friends colleagues throughout country. family stayed it.and, better worse, gay ex-husband me, always.
catalonia, church becomes place artistic pilgrimage child, barcelona-born painter santi moix often made weekend trips father saurí, remote catalan village 16 people perched high pyrenees. now, 57, moix perhaps closest thing saurí local celebrity, built career exhibiting work brooklyn museum milan’s m77 gallery, prada’s soho store (a 2013 commission) featuring abstract, hypersaturated flora fauna murals.five years ago, local government bishop asked artist might come paint interior st. victor, village’s 1,100-year-old romanesque church, whose plain stone walls become dull decrepit time. moix, isn’t religious, reluctant. finally, many months negotiations, agreed — he’d granted full artistic license, free conceptual obligations church state. “i clear would paint saints martyrs,” says.what ended producing largest piece date, 1,200 square feet frescoes cover church, describes “huge garden full fantasy.” new eden — painstakingly mapped brooklyn studio — abounds psychedelic daisies, spotted salamanders, beasts tentacles copulating sheep, rendered cloudlike swaths grass green, cornflower yellow strawberry pink. assistants sanded plastered st. victor’s walls (and covered mediocre art), moix spent three years saurí, on, painting scenes directly onto building’s surfaces 15 hours day using handmade boar-bristle brushes organic pigments diluted water. “like human skin tattoos,” says, “the colors continue absorb months come.”the motifs appear fauvist natural world central moix’s work, though says found inspiring opportunity strip place worship religious iconography. (st. victor, welcomed parishioners continuously since founding ninth century, closed transformation, open month.) “churches used strike fear images demons fire,” moix says. “i loved idea overwhelming colors instead.” catalan government diocese hired agree; members conceived residency — expand pair regional artists neglected catholic properties — way replacing once-vibrant biblical paintings filled hundreds churches region sold stolen.in painting st. victor, moix joining storied tradition: catholic church is, course, responsible much christian world’s greatest artistic endeavors. also part recent movement, one sees contemporary artists remaking religious spaces. earlier year, american painter julie mehretu converted out-of-use harlem church soaring studio made giant, 32-foot-wide paintings (now display san francisco museum modern art) occasionally hosted visitors. u.k.-based sculptor gareth neal designer chris eckersley recently reskinned one london church, neal hold solo show another march. winter, space inspired romanesque chapels designed late ellsworth kelly unveiled blanton museum art austin, tex.it’s easy dismiss projects opportunistic, way claiming magnificent buildings left behind increasingly godless times service art world’s love larger-than-life spectacle. moix sees commission way revive region — one currently fraught conflict — called home. “i want give something locals proud of,” says. occasionally, he’s painting, saurí residents popped in, offering approving nods, even prayers. moments, moix lets be.
women cracked wartime codes. fix tech today, too. died 2016 age 94, ann caracristi, first female deputy director national security agency, liked reminisce absurd stereotypes women contend back entered public service world war ii. chief among — found somewhat amusing — notion women intellectually gifted men.genius male trait, widely believed 1940s. thinking went men brilliant sex, women better suited tedious tasks requiring humble virtues like patience focus. typing, example. filing. — case caracristi, interviewed book female code breakers — sorting categorizing. 1942, newly graduated russell sage college, caracristi recruited work stuffy attic former girls’ school washington area converted secret military code-breaking office. staff, many young women like her, sorted reams intercepted japanese messages pioneered new techniques.caracristi’s brilliance soon announced itself: female boss, schoolteacher west virginia, broke code enabled american military pinpoint location japanese troops. caracristi would rise become one storied women national security agency.more 70 years war ended, astonishing see doubts re-emerge women’s ability high-level intellectual work. far put rest, old prejudice found new expression naysayers like james damore, google engineer, fired, suggested infamous memo women shut top jobs silicon valley “biologically” suited brain work tech.when americans think veterans veterans day — infrequently — often think acts valor fixed earlier era. story country’s female veterans, pressed service trying time, tell us lot challenges face today, contributions civilian women, like caracristi, played critical role wartime military effort.in certain important ways, early 1940s progressive, experimental era military recruited many quarters. era give us clues performing better sectors today. worst, costliest, bloodiest war american history, inclusive mind-set helped allies defeat nazis.women key number wartime advances, presence crucial intelligence communications, well arena combines both: signals intelligence, code breaking. world war ii war encrypted signals. armies navies fought distant corners globe, combatants developed myriad code cipher systems cloak radio telegraph communications, code breaking came way eavesdrop enemy plans.more half american code-breaking force female — roughly 10,000 women. many college graduates shut graduate schools excluded fields math engineering, place talents.even america’s formal entry war, women formed important part civilian staff clandestine offices attempting break japanese european systems. one genevieve grotjan, mathematician aspired teach college-level math unable find university math department willing hire her. joined team trying break “purple,” cipher-generating machine used japanese diplomats.the team labored year; september 1940, grotjan spotted coincidence broke cipher. breakthrough provided key intelligence entire war officials privy contents called “magic.”once attack pearl harbor brought america war, country’s code-breaking offices enlarged. men shipped overseas fast ships could get there, military leaders — congress — realized united states could staff multi-ocean war using men, women’s military groups created.women went work air traffic control towers and, despite fears would become hysterical crisis, kept wits. addition millions female factory workers, women ran radios radar, worked chemists, bacteriologists gunnery instructors — calculated weapon trajectories.those tested high aptitude routed two top-secret code-breaking centers washington area, one army one navy.other women joined office strategic services, forerunner c.i.a. vassar math professor, grace hopper, helped develop navy’s mark computer. team women programmed army’s first large-scale, general-purpose digital computer. (programming time considered somewhat secretarial, women employed it.)it’s much stretch say inclusion — willingness welcome genius — one reason right side war. country also benefited contributions marginalized groups, including navajo code talkers, tuskegee airmen black troops (including women) serving segregated military.there lesson tech bros. economists long mystified impulse discriminate, given shutting group deprives society advances. studies show diverse teams get better results. inclusion never entails “lowering bar.” enlarges pool talent brings best people in.to sure, even war, inclusion seen temporary emergency measure, spectacle tens thousands young women boarding trains nation’s capital unnerved many. ads posters featured plaintive children asking, “mother, stay home again?” war, backlash set in. female code breakers got little public credit achievements, credit would long time coming towering figures like grace hopper. are: notion genius male trait raised head.in today’s rhetorical climate, it’s handful entitled engineers feel empowered impugn certain groups. animus lies behind trump administration’s eagerness exclude refugees, behind proposed ban transgender people serving military. gratuitously acting exclude willing citizens military service, president declined avail array ingenuity courage nation offer.world war ii reminder that, freedom hung balance, inclusion kept us safe. it’s also reminder military took lead social change time families felt connected military service. greatly divided. we’re losing key military edge could lose technical one, give notion groups gifted others. history shown exclusion tends approach of, donald trump might put it, losers.
lesson biggest losers: exercise keeps weight question plagues struggle weight: us manage keep lost pounds, others regain them?now, study 14 participants “biggest loser” television show provides answer: physical activity — much public health guidelines suggest.on average, managed maintain significant weight loss 80 minutes day moderate activity, like walking, 35 minutes day vigorous exercise, like running.the researchers conducting new study distinguish purposeful exercise, like going gym working out, exercise done course day, like walking work taking stairs.guidelines centers disease control prevention, comparison, call least 150 minutes week moderate exercise, 75 minutes week vigorous exercise healthy adults.the study published tuesday journal obesity. lead author, kevin hall, chief integrative physiology section national institute diabetes digestive kidney diseases, colleagues also presented work obesity society’s annual meeting.although study small must replicated, dr. hall said, first assess obese people years lost weight state-of-the-art methods measure calories consumed amount exercise done.the researchers measurements contestants chosen, six weeks, 30 weeks six years contest began.“the findings important,” said rena wing, psychiatry professor brown university founder national weight control registry, includes 10,000 people.the food eaten “is key determinant initial weight loss. physical activity key maintenance,” said.the study also helps explain might be. one consequence weight loss among “biggest loser” participants greatly slowed metabolism.the subjects burning average 500 fewer calories day would expected, dr. hall colleagues found. essence, bodies fighting weight loss.those kept weight “are countering drop metabolism physical activity,” dr. hall said.during initial weight loss, equation different. then, difference much weight “biggest loser” contestants lost could explained number calories cut diets. amount exercise distinguish lost lost less.the contestants competed six months see could lose weight. participants followed grueling diet exhausting exercise program.contestants’ average weight start show 329 pounds. end, 200 pounds, 129-pound loss. six years study ended, average weight rebounded 290 pounds, 38 pounds less started.that average, though, hid wide variations.to learn more, dr. hall colleagues divided group 14 two. “regainers,” seven participants ended six years weighing five pounds average start.and “maintainers,” seven maintained average weight loss 81 pounds.to measure number calories contestants burned, researchers asked subjects drink “doubly labeled water,” hydrogen oxygen atoms least partially replaced stable isotopes, different atomic mass.the oxygen isotopes appear carbon dioxide exhaled subjects, allowed researchers estimate average amount exhaled day. calories burned, carbon dioxide exhaled.some “biggest loser” contestants — including first author, dr. jennifer kerns, obesity specialist veterans affairs medical center washington — said conclusions new study confirmed experiences.dr. kerns, contestant season 3 show, says managed keep 100 pounds tracking everything eats exercising elliptical cross-trainer 35 40 minutes day. addition, job requires walk around hospital seeing patients.she learned cannot relax regimen wants maintain weight. “my natural tendency regain,” said.erinn egbert candidate season 8 “biggest loser” ultimately make cut. went home “to figure own.”she hired two trainers followed diet exercise program finished senior year ohio state university. weighed 237 pounds show began lost 120 pounds.she maintained weight eight pounds more. rigid portion control regular, intense exercise — 45 minutes hour day, monday saturday, beachbody programs, challenging combination strength training cardiovascular exercise.ms. egbert, 30 lives lexington, ky., says learned importance working consistently stay thin, even slowed metabolism.“you got keep every single day,” said.it’s difficult task virtually anyone, dr. kerns said: “the amount time dedication takes manage one’s food intake prioritize exercise every day untenable burden many people.”“it’s totally unfair judge can’t it,” added.dr. hall agreed. “the idea people regain lost weight necessarily slothful gluttonous unfortunate stigmatization based fact,” said.danny cahill, 47 lives tulsa, okla., among found increasingly difficult keep sort regimen needed avoid gaining weight.he “biggest loser” competition season 8. weighed 430 pounds show began, lost 239 them.for four years show, exercised two half hours day gained back 40 pounds.then injuries began, forcing cut back workouts one half hours day. weight crept 235 pounds.the next year, “my body started breaking down,” said. “i foot injury, wrist injury. couldn’t keep up.” exhausted.his weight went 300 pounds. last two years, weight remained stable 340 350 pounds, “but eating little can,” said.“that’s disheartening part,” mr. cahill said. losing pounds one thing. keeping off?“i still struggling it,” said.
