explains u.s. mass shootings? international comparisons suggest answer world looks united states, sees land exceptions: time-tested noisy democracy, crusader foreign policy, exporter beloved music film.but one quirk consistently puzzles america’s fans critics alike. why, ask, experience many mass shootings?perhaps, speculate, american society unusually violent. racial divisions frayed bonds society. citizens lack proper mental care health care system draws frequent derision abroad.these explanations share one thing common: though seemingly sensible, debunked research shootings elsewhere world. instead, ever-growing body research consistently reaches conclusion.the variable explain high rate mass shootings america astronomical number guns.the top-line numbers suggest correlation that, investigation, grows clearer.americans make 4.4 percent global population 42 percent world’s guns. 1966 2012, 31 percent gunmen mass shootings worldwide american, according 2015 study adam lankford, professor university alabama.adjusted population, yemen higher rate mass shootings among countries 10 million people — distinction mr. lankford urged avoid outliers. yemen world’s second-highest rate gun ownership united states.worldwide, mr. lankford found, country’s rate gun ownership correlated odds would experience mass shooting. relationship held even excluded united states, indicating could explained factor particular home country. held controlled homicide rates, suggesting mass shootings better explained society’s access guns baseline level violence.if mental health made difference, data would show americans mental health problems people countries fewer mass shootings. mental health care spending rate united states, number mental health professionals per capita rate severe mental disorders line wealthy countries.a 2015 study estimated 4 percent american gun deaths could attributed mental health issues. mr. lankford, email, said countries high suicide rates tended low rates mass shootings — opposite would expect mental health problems correlated mass shootings.whether population plays fewer video games also appears impact. americans likely play video games people developed country.racial diversity factors associated social cohesion also show little correlation gun deaths. among european countries, little association immigration diversity metrics rates gun murders mass shootings.america’s gun homicide rate 33 per million people 2009, far exceeding average among developed countries. canada britain, 5 per million 0.7 per million, respectively, also corresponds differences gun ownership.americans sometimes see expression deeper problems crime, notion ingrained, part, series films portraying urban gang violence early 1990s. united states actually prone crime developed countries, according landmark 1999 study franklin e. zimring gordon hawkins university california, berkeley.rather, found, data since repeatedly confirmed, american crime simply lethal. new yorker likely robbed londoner, instance, new yorker 54 times likely killed process.they concluded discrepancy, like many anomalies american violence, came guns.more gun ownership corresponds gun murders across virtually every axis: among developed countries, among american states, among american towns cities controlling crime rates. gun control legislation tends reduce gun murders, according recent analysis 130 studies 10 countries.this suggests guns cause violence.skeptics gun control sometimes point 2016 study. 2000 2014, found, united states death rate mass shooting 1.5 per one million people. rate 1.7 switzerland 3.4 finland, suggesting american mass shootings actually common.but study found united states 133 mass shootings. finland two, killed 18 people, switzerland one, killed 14. short, isolated incidents. mass shootings happen anywhere, matter routine united states.as crime, underlying risk impossible fully erase. individual snap become entranced violent ideology. different likelihood lead mass murder.in china, dozen seemingly random attacks schoolchildren killed 25 people 2010 2012. used knives; none used gun.by contrast, window, united states experienced five deadliest mass shootings, killed 78 people. scaled population, american attacks 12 times deadly.in 2013, american gun-related deaths included 21,175 suicides, 11,208 homicides 505 deaths caused accidental discharge. year japan, country one-third america’s population, guns involved 13 deaths.this means american 300 times likely die gun homicide accident japanese person. america’s gun ownership rate 150 times high japan’s. gap 150 300 shows gun ownership statistics alone explain makes america different.the united states also weakest controls may buy gun sorts guns may owned.switzerland second-highest gun ownership rate developed country, half united states. gun homicide rate 2004 7.7 per million people — unusually high, keeping relationship gun ownership murders, still fraction rate united states.swiss gun laws stringent, setting higher bar securing keeping license, selling guns types guns owned. laws reflect tighter restrictions. imply different way thinking guns, something citizens must affirmatively earn right own.the united states one three countries, along mexico guatemala, begin opposite assumption: people inherent right guns.the main reason american regulation gun ownership weak may fact trade-offs simply given different weight united states anywhere else.after britain mass shooting 1987, country instituted strict gun control laws. australia 1996 shooting. united states repeatedly faced calculus determined relatively unregulated gun ownership worth cost society.that choice, statistic regulation, sets united states apart.“in retrospect sandy hook marked end us gun control debate,” dan hodges, british journalist, wrote post twitter two years ago, referring 2012 attack killed 20 young students elementary school connecticut. “once america decided killing children bearable, over.”
vast indigenous land claims canada encompass parliament hill pikwakanagan first nation, ontario — whenever prime minister justin trudeau cabinet ministers speak certain parts ontario quebec, begin acknowledging “unceded algonquin territory.”that recognition one ways mr. trudeau’s government trying signal top priority: righting wrongs canada done indigenous people, especially land aboriginals say taken unjustly.but finding common ground issue proved one mr. trudeau’s difficult policy initiatives, critics say efforts resolve land disputes bogged down. sides agree importance sorting claims.“the process negotiating land claims absolute pillar reconciliation,” said ken coates, historian university saskatchewan studies treaties consultant indigenous groups. “this chance get right don’t — boy, get chance again?”of many issues dividing canada’s federal provincial governments indigenous people, land claims among symbolically important economically consequential, often involving vast amounts land.some claims involve hundreds millions dollars, tribes often interested controlling land issue, by, example, say logging, oil exploration mining.one claim various algonquin groups involves 8.9 million acres ottawa watershed — includes canada’s parliament buildings supreme court. government thought settled claim principle year ago, ended litigation anyway.the claims legally thorny, often requiring historians, archaeologists, geographers geologists give evidence sometimes stretching back recorded history support, challenge, them.in regions, land may occupied different indigenous groups different times, even changing hands battles unrecorded. groups may assert rights, claims overlap.then problem treaties. indigenous groups, like algonquins, never signed treaties giving land. government says talking 140 indigenous groups situation.others sign treaties, government tribunal deals treaty disputes 72 cases overwhelmed cannot estimate long take resolve them.the result settlement negotiations o