chinese village keeps alive tradition indigo dyeing dali village, china — young woman sat foot wooden loom began weave. fingers passed orange shuttle back forth delicate cotton threads, creaky contraption sprang life.yang xiuying — plucky woman taller loom — peered granddaughter’s shoulder, inspecting newly emerging fabric flaws. ever since young girl, ms. yang, 74, weaving dyeing indigo textiles using techniques ethnic dong southern chinese province guizhou passed mother daughter generations.“you can’t buy type handmade cloth market,” ms. yang said, patting bolt gleaming indigo-colored cloth wrinkled, navy-stained hands.here dali, ancient village nestled verdant hills, making indigo cloth long part life, less important dong farming rice fermenting fish.even era fast fashion, many dong women still devote countless hours making dark, glossy cloth. fabric must woven, wrung, scrubbed pounded used create traditional dong cotton garments — dark navy costumes colorful flower trim women plain indigo men.“for dong family, loom important cow,” said lai lei, founder weaving dyeing co-op nearby village. “as children, grow listening sound loom.”dyeing woven dali’s culture practice even survived cultural revolution, many dong traditions, shamanism, stamped communist fanatics trying destroy saw feudal past.but traditions come different threat since china’s market economy took recent decades. lure work education drawn youth china’s growing cities, young dong women left villages like one.of remain, even fewer show interest learning labor-intensive techniques indigo dyeing.“i want teach daughters, don’t want learn,” said zhang yuyuan, 75, stepped back plunging fabric navy-blue bath. “they say, ‘we’ll mess up, it.’”hoping save dali’s folk traditions, provincial officials 2011 invited global heritage fund, preservation organization based california.the global heritage fund begun working atlas studio, beijing-based design studio, set weaving dyeing co-op dali. aim twofold: create opportunities work closer home persuade young dong women learn traditions.“for long time, guizhou known one strongest cultural resources ethnic minority villages,” said kuanghan li, china program director global heritage fund. “now rural villages hot topic china.”tourism yet take dali, though may matter time. unlike many villages china preservation undertaken heavy hand, village feel untouched oasis, due part remote location.even today, accessible narrow mountain road winds lush bamboo forests descending valley sloping gray-tiled rooftops huddle closely together.a recent visit village found hundred residents hard work. nearly every family grows rice indigo, ready harvest.in busy autumn mornings, dong women wake first. roosters still asleep sky dark yang xiukui stepped outside start day’s work. folded long length indigo cloth lay onto flat stone surface.using heavy wooden mallet, ms. yang, 55, began pound fabric. thump, cloth grew brighter, acquiring shiny gloss. luster — achieved application cowhide extract and, times, egg whites — prized dong women. wear handmade indigo clothes holidays festivals, women inspect sheen one another’s handiwork spirit friendly competition.as ms. yang worked, chorus roosters joined plinking mallets awaken village. sleepy children stumbled school along stone-paved paths older people kibitzed doorsteps traditional wooden homes.ms. yang brought now-gleaming indigo cloth covered plastic tub corner still dark kitchen. removed lid, releasing pungent, fermented odor. inside dark blue, frothy liquid.almost every dong woman 40 plastic tub hold indigo dye bath. tradition, placement tub within house crucial, must made according principles feng shui, ancient practice arranging objects improve one’s luck.one year, ms. yang said, placed tub another part house, realizing bad feng shui. dye — made mixture indigo leaves, rice alcohol, wild plants lye — ruined, said.dong women believe factors spoil dye. women pregnant menstruating, example, expected stay away. ms. li global heritage fund recounted one time became apparent dye bath ruined cloth wasn’t turning color.“all women looked around said, ‘o.k., pregnant?’” said.ms. yang plunged fabric dye bath, making sure soak section thoroughly. several rounds soaking drip-drying later, hung heavy cloth wooden pole dry. quick meal chili fermented fish, sautéed vegetables rice, hopped onto back husband’s motorbike headed full day harvesting rice fields. 9 a.m.the next morning, ms. yang repeated entire process. total, takes dong women two weeks color single bolt cloth desired rich shade indigo.“they say whoever darkest stains hands makes best cloth,” ms. yang said proudly, held purple-streaked hands.
