trans-pacific trade partners moving on, without u.s. hong kong — president trump shook world economic order year pulling united states major international trade pact raising fundamental questions global role.today, world moving without it.a group 11 countries announced saturday committed resurrecting sweeping multinational trade agreement, trans-pacific partnership, without united states. new deal, would signed ratified country, would include major united states allies like japan, canada mexico. collectively, account sixth global trade.the agreement “serve foundation building broader free-trade area” across asia, taro kono, japan’s foreign minister, said statement.pointedly, potential members called comprehensive progressive agreement trans-pacific partnership came early agreement broad outline deal many leaders meeting mr. trump vietnam — potential member new trading group.some details new deal, including rules would phased in, still need determined, prospective member states like canada raised last-minute concerns. new deal could announced soon early next year.other countries slowly surely making progress sweeping trade deals, without participation united states. china negotiating potential deal 16 asia-pacific countries, including japan, india south korea. european union japan hope strike separate trade pacts group south american countries, brazil argentina among them.from tough talk china (“they took jobs”) casting doubt decades-old north american free trade agreement (“the worst trade deal ever made”), mr. trump threatened lob grenade increasingly integrated global economic system.his administration questioned years efforts lower global trade barriers, arguing hurt american workers led big trade deficits. also means dealing nations one-on-one, rejecting regional global pacts predecessors pursued.but factors pushing rest world fill void left united states. china’s rise regional economic power driving nations either join join together counter it. fast development places like southeast asia means potential new markets kinds products. absence united states means potential opportunities others.“at point, administration may begin see strategic mistake dropping trade interest american workers,” said rufus yerxa, president national foreign trade council, lobbying group represents companies like walmart, ford microsoft.“we’ve got compete winner global markets — danger is, strategy divisive,” added.more worrying possibility trump administration ceding position global leader china, rising economic political influence region.“the u.s. lost leadership role,” said jayant menon, economist asian development bank. “and china quickly replacing it.”under new trans-pacific trade deal, members would enjoy tariff-free trade one another. would allow companies member countries faster better access markets american rivals.but still challenges ahead group, prospective member states meeting danang, vietnam, complete accord finer details new deal.“we pleased progress made towards possible agreement, still work done,” françois-philippe champagne, canada’s minister international trade, said statement. added canada would sign deal interests addressed.even without united states, deal would largest trade agreement history. intended increase protections intellectual property countries, opening markets free trade agricultural products digital services around region. also provisions improving working conditions, although debate likely results.in statement posted online, australian government said agreement principle demonstrated 11 countries’ “commitment open markets, combat protectionism advance regional economic integration.”the 11 countries working toward new agreement japan, australia, canada, mexico, singapore, malaysia, vietnam, chile, peru, new zealand brunei.mr. trump expressed support nation’s regional allies even rejects criticizes trade deals them. reiterated american support cooperation security stops japan south korea.in china, went way woo president xi jinping, going far suggest trade deficit united states fault past american administrations rather china itself.“i don’t blame china,” mr. trump said tweet friday morning shortly leaving vietnam.“the u.s. driving force, behind global economic order, also pursuing higher standards free trade securing provisions go way world trade organization obligations,” said stephen olson, former united states trade negotiator worked nafta. “if u.s. abdicates role, puts us uncharted territory,” added.in absence american leadership, japan driven new round talks. prime minister shinzo abe spoken countries working agreement ocean’s eleven, movie.japan’s long-term hope united states eventually return fold.“we go ahead make welcome united states back decide so,” said ichiro fujisaki, former japanese ambassador washington. completing deal now, said, “makes possibility u.s. coming back likely.”the new agreement crafted hope united states one day participate. provisions — among ones united states lobbied — could ultimately suspended, including copyright protection.given intensity mr. trump excoriated original deal, seems unlikely administration come back table.“it difficult administration backtrack,” said wendy cutler, former united states trade negotiator worked trans-pacific deal managing director washington office asia society policy institute.but countries like korea, philippines thailand expected join deal ratified, said ms. cutler.for members, pact could offer sense security time number politicians around world questioning impact trade globalization.speaking last week, prime minister malcolm turnbull australia said deal promised “greater transparency stronger rule law, world dangerously short both,” referring “siren songs populists, advocating protectionism.”“the t.p.p. creates rules road match new economic world living in,” mr. turnbull said.notably, trans-pacific pact includes mexico canada, loggerheads trump administration nafta. mr. trump raised prospect demise agreement, citing movement industrial jobs united states countries.“there genuine risk u.s. going disengage regional economic interaction,” said christopher nelson, editor nelson report, foreign policy trade newsletter. “and corporate standpoint, american companies disadvantaged competitively we’re feet playing game.”
