battered tattered, puerto rico’s flag still waves mike vargas knows deal wrecks, even ones could take years. cars repairs soups inside northeast bronx auto body shop, east coast customs automotive playground, seem like easy fixes compared devastation puerto rico, family property. now, works cars, vibrant mural looms him, constantly reminding dire human challenges. suggesting famous photograph, “raising flag iwo jima,” mural depicts hard-hatted workers lifting flag-topped utility pole devastated landscape.not mr. vargas needs reminders. puerto rican new yorker, always thinking island’s humanitarian crisis. within days hurricane maria, group local body shop owners started collecting water emergency supplies, shipped island two cargo containers. though urgency situation may fading headlines, resolve not.“once thanksgiving hits, people going forget,” mr. vargas lamented. “when look wall tells we’re down. we’re rebuilding. we’re going get better. it’s like 9/11. want forget.”the mural created two graffiti artists: alfredo oyague, better known per one fx crew, alfred bennett, known royal kingbee. years, mr. oyague painted various murals shop, planning redo waiting room weeks ago mr. vargas’ request. mr. vargas suggested something based crisis puerto rico, mr. oyague showed image friend found online, recovery workers portrayed figures joe rosenthal’s iwo jima photo.“i told him, ‘yo mike, beautiful image it’s awesome statement, won’t fit waiting room,’” mr. oyague recalled. “he immediately fell love gave us big wall inside shop.”like many puerto ricans, mr. vargas felt federal response slow inadequate, situation made worse president trump’s twitter feed, reminded people cash-strapped island already “billions dollars” debt “wall street banks.” $4.9 billion federal aid proposed help island’s government pay bills, came loan.“it’s like owe money, shouldn’t get help.” mr. vargas said. “it’s like turned backs us.”mr. oyague deeply personal reasons inspired work mural. mother ana, 72, retired metropolitan transportation authority bus driver, lived barranquitas, hard-hit mountain town halfway san juan ponce. planned ride storm along sister, 85-year-old nun. brick house solid, immune wind water. prepare storm, moved generator ruptured disc back. then, hurricane, condition worsened.“the storm blew sliding door mom trying push back, wind strong,” mr. oyague said. “she blew back, let door go went bedroom sister. got top bed place started flood. nothing wait out.”even though waters receded, took eight days roads cleared. aunt staying religious order’s philadelphia convent, mother — using wheelchair back heals — moved apartment soundview section bronx, mr. oyague also lives. time uncertain exile, thoughts remain fixed many relatives island, like one uncle lives close mother’s house barranquitas.“we’re losing him,” mr. oyague said. “he’s well since depending himself. light water bad diabetes little bit — no, lot — drinking problem. can’t fend himself. don’t think he’s going make holidays.”given complicated history united states island territory, mr. oyague sees mural political statement many relate personal level. still seething mr. trump’s brief — limited — visit island, tossed rolls paper towels crowd.“that degrading,” said. “he thinks us second-rate citizens. we’re dependent upon u.s. u.s. purposely made us dependent them. needed use us. lot good traits don’t want people forget that.”mr. oyague thought strong, positive image could help inspire puerto ricans community. “it shows us rebuilding giving up. puerto rican flag still waving. even though island obliterated, we’re still here.”
david dinkins doesn’t think failed. might right. david n. dinkins became 106th mayor new york jan. 1, 1990, pledging “toughest mayor crime city ever seen.” day, 12 people murdered city. four years later, mr. dinkins lost bid re-election, beginning contested legacy still generate argument.“david dinkins failed mayor,” begins 2012 biography mr. dinkins.“david dinkins leader look to,” hillary clinton said 2015, adding mr. dinkins “helped lay foundation dramatic drops crime.”so goes complicated late career david dinkins, office slightest margins rudolph w. giuliani, lost man four years later. critics, symbolizes bad old days unchecked crime, racial tension fiscal anarchy. supporters, began turnaround successors still take credit. new yorkers voted overwhelmingly re-elect mayor bill de blasio week, part vote values rejected.what mean succeed fail mayor new york city? former mayor live amid judgment?on recent afternoon office columbia university, mr. dinkins sat surrounded plaques photographs celebrating highlights career, world apart arrows filled days. 90, african-american mayor city’s history, former mayor one quarter life, three times long held elective office. across desk new york newsday headline celebrating “mayor cool.”“i sit sometimes look reminisce,” mr. dinkins said, nodding toward photograph harry belafonte, friend. men turned 90 year. “he m.c. inauguration,” mr. dinkins said. “he one said me: ‘you run. must run.’ insisted run mayor.”mr. dinkins wore red patterned bow tie blue double-breasted suit, filled since stopped playing tennis years ago. talked, daughter called ask whether seen doctor nagging pain knee, alarm cellphone, programmed grandson, reminded take several medications. would wait; left home.he noted unique place new york lore. mayors face criticism problems linger leave office; mr. dinkins’s critics focus problems quickly abated.“the new york times probably obit now,” said, raising grievance aired before. spoke courtly formality, quick set piece score settle. “i always used say, they’ll say, ‘david dinkins, first black mayor city new york,’ next sentence crown heights,” brooklyn neighborhood four-day riot broke watch, widely criticized.would unfair?“in way,” said. “i don’t say it’s unfair, things accurate greater moment. think overall pretty good job. things went well, didn’t always get credit entitled, things go well, you’re mayor, it’s fault. still greatest job world.”in 2013, bill de blasio running first democratic mayor since mr. dinkins — two-decade drought city democrats outnumber republicans six one — state republican chairman, edward f. cox, warned mr. de blasio “is going take city back dinkins era,” adding, “the dinkins era crime grime high welfare rolls, that’s what’s going happen city.”david dinkins always code word bad old days. son housekeeper barber, raised segregated schools trenton, n.j., entered new york politics powerful harlem democratic clubhouse, formed alliances charles rangel, basil a. paterson percy e. sutton — “gang four” city’s african-american power structure. ran mayor 1989, figure civility healing.at time, first african-american mayors office los angeles, philadelphia, detroit, oakland baltimore; black mayors governed atlanta, newark washington, d.c., well. rev. jesse jackson carried new york city 1988 democratic presidential primary. new york seemed due.the city, turn, needed healing. recent racially charged attacks white jogger central park black teenager fleeing white mob bensonhurst, brooklyn, skyrocketing murder rate exacerbated crack trade, created image city control, ungovernable. wall street still reeling black monday crash 1987, city government faced budget shortfalls $1 billion.mr. dinkins arrived office wave hope, said wilbur c. rich, professor emeritus wellesley college author “david dinkins new york city politics.”“i excited, many black people excited see he’d do,” mr. rich said. “there triumphalism. there’s far go that. wears off, he’s mayor. lot us thought would something police department. didn’t that. lot us thought would demonstrate white community black people competent manage city size.”mr. dinkins’s first year saw record numbers murders major crimes, fiscal crisis, high levels homelessness city hall seemed disarray, staffers battling one another leaking press.but second year, crime began long decline imagined possible. mr. dinkins added cops streets — wangling tax increase — cadets police academy, went duty left office. averted fiscal takeover state, began remarkable transformation times square, returned public libraries six-day weeks, opened schools night community use expanded national tennis center flushing meadows, queens, city’s 108th mayor, michael r. bloomberg, called “the good athletic sports stadium deal, new york country.”“overall think bad,” mr. dinkins said.yet mayors succeed fail halls government also public imagination, said kenneth t. jackson, editor “the encyclopedia new york city” history professor columbia.“i think dinkins’s heart right place, didn’t create image someone who’s strong,” mr. jackson said. “koch giuliani, book-ended dinkins, seemed powerful, take-charge. whether wrong right policy new york different issue.”nor mr. dinkins, promised healer, mollify black leaders potential allies. civil rights activist c. vernon mason called mr. dinkins “traitor,” alton maddox called “an ed koch blackface”; fernando ferrer, democratic city councilman, called “maddeningly slow”; al sharpton called uncle tom “whore turning tricks city hall.” jewish leaders accused allowing black mobs attack jews crown heights. even newspaper’s endorsement mr. dinkins second term called “disengaged,” undisciplined, “slow react” “maddeningly phlegmatic.”numbers stories, though sometimes get turned them. one story, homicides fell 13 percent mr. dinkins’s tenure, record high 2,245 first year 1,946 last. another, 1,946 killings mark city still crisis. (last year 335.)successful mayors inhabit first story; failed mayors live one.“the key thing dinkins years sense fear,” said fred siegel, scholar residence st. francis college contributing editor conservative city journal, former adviser mr. giuliani. “crime fell, fell marginally. people panicked. response crime ineffectual.”asked mr. dinkins’s impact city, mr. siegel said: “he made possible moderately conservative mayor elected new york. turned competent mayor we’ve since la guardia.”at heart david dinkins’s story mayor four days august 1991, car rabbi’s motorcade crown heights ran red light killed 7-year-old guyanese boy named gavin cato.the neighborhood exploded. angry black residents assailed driver, escaped via volunteer jewish ambulance crew. two hours later, crowd surrounded stabbed rabbinical student named yankel rosenbaum, died wound noticed hospital.three days mayhem followed, bands black residents taking streets, chanting “heil hitler” “kill jews,” jewish residents accusing black mayor permitting “pogrom,” organized massacre ethnic group. crowds hurled bricks bottles police patrols, forcing run lives; mayor police commissioner also came attack. network news reports showed buildings police cars fire, mayor appeared powerless — said unwilling — restore order.finally, mayor police department changed tactics, negotiating arresting combatants. fires crowds dissipated. news cameras went home. damage done.in office quarter-century later, mr. dinkins dismissed question whether, changed tactics one night sooner, might re-election.“you don’t know fact,” said. “i said police brass, whatever guys doing, ain’t working. need get together. whether police thought wanted lenient blacks attacking jews — can’t imagine would thought — case. got accused that, that’s painful.”had won, turn, place history might different, said john h. mollenkopf, director center urban research graduate center city university new york. police cadets authorized would hit streets watch; crime might really dropped, mr. giuliani, aided end crack epidemic; walt disney company’s restoration new amsterdam theater 1997, began transformation 42nd street (the deal started mr. dinkins closed mr. giuliani), would lifted mayoralty.mr. dinkins declined speculate. “the action one takes circumstance like ought based get votes lose votes,” said. “it ought based right thing do. everybody’s whole lot smarter fact.”new yorkers always love mayors. mr. de blasio, july poll quinnipiac university, approval rating 50 percent, 46 percent respondents saying deserved re-election. three years office, mr. bloomberg approval rating 43 percent.neither met real resistance re-election. mr. giuliani finished first term 62 percent approval rating, sunk badly second, rebounded dynamism attacks sept. 11, 2001.mr. de blasio, junior staffer mr. dinkins, said mr. dinkins’s problem image created tabloids, still loud powerful early ’90s.“dinkins got raw deal largely race,” mr. de blasio said telephone interview re-election. “and got raw deal loud, showy personality wasn’t always trying claim credit. normal assessment history would say, wait minute, added cops, that’s turned around.”“the thing learned audacity deal appeared intractable problem,” mr. de blasio added. “the fact we’re safest big city america today directly links actions getting resources albany get us size police force needed.“none predecessors figured it. i’m sure successor, took lot credit work done resources dinkins got — i’m sure successor could pulled albany political reality.”yet mr. dinkins failed, among voters time. winning election 1989 50 percent vote, lost 1993 50 percent, difference often attributed surge voter turnout staten island, voters ballot initiative secede city. almost well regarded four years taking office. neither election win one third white voters, even though democratic opponent races, mr. giuliani, political experience lot rough edges.in mr. dinkins’s 2013 autobiography, attributed loss “just racism, pure simple.”j. phillip thompson iii, worked mr. dinkins’s administration teaches urban politics massachusetts institute technology, said mr. dinkins’s true legacy coming fruition now.“a lot things de blasio successful around, emphasis affordable housing universal pre-k, things dinkins pushed hard,” mr. thompson said. “also, way went crime issue much deeper approach community policing giuliani had, time approaches proved effective. avoid issues got stop frisk police chokings. dinkins worked hard develop strong relationships police community.“he doesn’t get credit lot things,” added. “giuliani took credit reducing crime, isn’t one hired 5,000 cops $3 billion budget gap. narrative tends skip that.”in defeat, mr. dinkins became second new york mayor last century lose re-election single four-year term. this, too, legacy live with. him, black mayor major american city failed win second term.“i’m sure people think today,” mr. dinkins said dryly. “i think re-election. can’t answer didn’t. matter, could argued never first place, did. people infinite wisdom determined great american mayor, rudy giuliani.”he added, “we didn’t go job saying, well, can’t solve problems crime, can’t solve problems homelessness. everything thought could do. overall think bad.”his two successors, mr. giuliani mr. bloomberg, courted run president, largely differences cities mr. dinkins’s. mr. giuliani promised inauguration, “the era fear long-enough reign,” end first term, reign returned.even now, said letitia james, re-elected public advocate nov. 7, new yorkers contentious agree upon dinkins legacy. ms. james, studied mr. dinkins columbia, became first african-american woman hold citywide office elected public advocate 2013. said distinction, like city’s first black mayor, “nothing historical footnote, particularly don’t reach across form coalitions others.”still, mr. thompson, m.i.t. professor former dinkins staffer, said history would kind old boss. recent years, city named historic harlem tennis court him, well manhattan municipal building downtown david dinkins circle flushing meadows, near tennis stadium.“if look blacks, latinos progressive whites, 80 percent cities they’re majority now,” mr. thompson said. “and dinkins symbolized beginning that.“whether agree everything said kind secondary. point was, this. david dinkins didn’t elect himself. african-american community, latino community, progressive white community this. dinkins, again.“the message change. it’s possible. that’s dinkins symbolized.”
