review: ‘the band’s visit’ ravishing musical whispers romance breaking news broadway theatergoers, even — perhaps especially — thought past age infatuation: time fall love again.one ravishing musicals ever seduced opened thursday night barrymore theater. called “the band’s visit,” undeniable allure hard-charging, brightly blaring sort common box-office extravaganzas.instead, portrait single night tiny israeli desert town confirms lyric arrives, like nearly everything remarkable show, breath reluctantly romantic hope: “nothing beautiful something don’t expect.”with songs david yazbek script itamar moses, “the band’s visit” broadway rarity seldom found days outside canon stephen sondheim: honest-to-god musical grown-ups. work punctuated rowdy cheers foot-stomping ovations, despite uncanny virtuosity mr. yazbek’s benchmark score.that would stop show, really don’t want happen. directed david cromer inspired inventiveness never calls attention itself, “the band’s visit” flows grave joyful insistence life itself. asks quiet enough hear music murmurs, whispers silences human existence mundane — transcendent.and, oh yes, willing heart broken, least little. “the band’s visit,” stars magnificent katrina lenk tony shalhoub would-be lovers not-quite paradise, like life way, too.there worries finely detailed show, based eran kolirin’s screenplay 2007 film title, might survive transfer broadway. first staged sold-out houses late last year atlantic theater company, exuded shimmering transparency might well evaporated less intimate quarters.yet “the band’s visit” — follows modest adventures touring egyptian band stranded israeli village significant insignificance — holds larger stage. impeccably coordinated creative team magnified polished assets high sheen never feels synthetic.this show always close perfect musically. (mr. yazbek’s quietly simmering score, inflects broadway balladry character songs haunting middle eastern accent, felt essential oxygen.) felt shade less persuasive