joe biden talks new memoir, ‘promise me, dad’ joe biden’s new memoir, “promise me, dad,” time — sweep fullness. instead written fearsome ticktock seconds, minutes hours backs wall, obstacles faced.in substance, classic “year life” memoir. book starts thanksgiving 2014 covers three signal story lines next year: grueling illness death elder son, beau, brain cancer 46; difficult decision pursue democratic nomination president 2016; welcome workload vice president, particularly foreign crises iraq, ukraine central america.scene scene, biden toggles briskly among three story lines: emotional family meeting m.d. anderson cancer center houston, urgent phone call iraqi prime minister haider al-abadi islamic state, friendly lunch president obama, tactfully trying discourage vice president pursuing democratic nomination. leaping strand strand, biden creates propulsive energy distinct hope things may turn differently — better — know will.“promise me, dad” may probing president obama’s bildungsroman, “dreams father,” thoroughly thorough (at 494 pages) hillary clinton’s “what happened.” impressive terms. section section, biden splices heartbreaking story election story foreign affairs story. doing, offers something everyone, matter strand draws in.of course, centerpiece book biden’s unflinching account death son, two-term attorney general major national guard deployed iraq 2008. here, biden exudes everyman quality that’s display 40 years public life. shares grief, knowing everyone grieves. ultimately, message this: engaging life, bewildering may seem tragedy, thrive again.last month, biden sat book-lined study home leafy neighborhood wilmington, del., discuss memoir, published nov. 14.philip galanes: write book? tear heart open again?joe biden: kids. look, two beautiful grandchildren. thousand pictures around. year, building home, lived here: beau, [his wife] hallie two kids. wish they’d never moved. died, kids would come bed lie chest: “pop, tell stories daddy.” “tell one fell 