six myths choosing college major many colleges ask choose major early senior year high school, admissions application. yet there’s good chance you’ll change mind. education department says 30 percent students switch majors least once.students get plenty advice picking major. turns out, though, family friends, according september gallup survey. 11 percent sought guidance high school counselor, 28 percent college adviser. didn’t think advice especially helpful. maybe it’s much conventional thinking majors wrong.it’s true computer science engineering top pay rankings, salaries within specific majors vary greatly.“students parents pretty good idea majors pay most, poor sense magnitude differences within major,” said douglas a. webber, associate professor economics temple university studies earnings academic field. points one example: top quarter earners majored english make lifetimes bottom quarter chemical engineers.but never make top pay scale? even english history graduates make median lifetime earnings major pretty well compared typical graduates business stem field.take median lifetime earnings business majors, popular undergraduate degree. typical graduate earns $2.86 million lifetime. put business graduates side side graduated considered low-paying majors, you’ll see slightly median salary fields far behind business grads. example, english major 60th percentile makes $2.76 million lifetime, major psychology $2.57 million history major $2.64 million.women clear majority college campuses, making 56 percent students enrolled fall. also likely men graduate.but comes selecting major, women choose tends segregate lower paying fields, education social services, according report georgetown university’s center education workforce publish later year. look highest paying fields proportion women major them: business economics (31 percent), chemical engineering (28 percent), computer science (20 percent), electrical engineering (10 percent), mechanical engineering (8 percent)