10 things know getting dream college there’s magic formula getting selective college, decade covering admissions chronicle higher education, i’ve picked thing two. takeaways, based hundreds interviews admissions deans years, may help navigate process.when colleges choose applicants, they’re juggling competing goals, like increasing diversity bringing revenue. admissions officers aren’t looking students fit one description — say, who’ve earned a’s awards. don’t take rejection personally.colleges often say want get know real you, that’s probably true academic accomplishments (and rigor courses you’ve taken) pass muster.after colleges identify big batch students outstanding credentials, differences among become important, admissions deans say. among attributes tell would like see evidence (in essays, extracurricular activities, recommendations) are: leadership, risk taking, emotional intelligence, fire learning, critical thinking, curiosity, empathy, optimism, grit, perseverance ability overcome obstacles.overwhelmed slick, boastful essays, colleges eager call “authentic” glimpses applicants — experiences, passions goals. deans believe they’ll get deeper insight alternative formats like videos, pictures, audio files documents (an advanced placement english paper, maybe). handful prestigious schools, including yale, university chicago, pomona college, reed college university rochester, recently introduced option. essays, much polish good, deans say, might think twice hiring professional videographer. yale, 400 applicants (out nearly 33,000) year’s freshman class sent something alternative format. least one case, submission — video showing leadership impact others — was, dean told me, “difference maker.”are first-generation low-income student? many colleges trying increase access, help emphasize background — personal story relates achievements — essays interviews. admissions officers thinking harder socioeconomic context, quality applicant’s high school, better understand opportunities they’ve challenges they’ve faced.at many colleges, financial circumstances comes play. able pay freight bonus. qualified students limited means might get rejected reason lack money.many selective colleges want students over, ideally 50 states. last year’s presidential election illuminated urban-rural divide, colleges trying bridge paying closer attention promising applicants less-populous areas. generally, northeastern college look favorably applicant montana equally strong one northeast.legacy status certainly helps, big-name colleges reject plenty applicants. don’t assume mom dad’s connections alone get in.a new initiative called “turning tide” urges admissions offices reward applicants sustained community service. colleges, massachusetts institute technology, taking closer look applicants done help others, neighbors family members. don’t fly belize good (admissions officers often skeptical fleeting trips). showing tutor someone library week might even impressive, rewarding.about one five colleges allot “considerable importance” “demonstrated interest,” whereby applicants convey willingness attend college they’re applying to. open emails. connect admissions officers. let know visit campus. sure first choice don’t need compare financial aid packages choose strongest expression demonstrated interest: applying early decision, binding.
endowments boom colleges bury earnings overseas 2006, endowments indiana university texas christian university invested millions dollars partnership, hoping mint riches oil, gas coal.the partnership formed houston-based quintana capital group, whose principals include donald l. evans, influential texan longtime supporter former president george w. bush. little year earlier, mr. evans left cabinet position commerce secretary.though group impressive texas pedigree, presidential cachet ambitions operations united states, new partnership established cayman islands. founders promised university nonprofit investors partnership would try avoid federal taxes exploiting loophole called “blocker corporations,” typically established tax havens around world.a trove millions leaked documents bermuda-based law firm, appleby, reflects tax wizardry used american colleges universities. schools increasingly turned secretive offshore investments, files show, let swell endowments blocker corporations, avoid scrutiny ventures involving fossil fuels issues could set campus controversy.buoyed lucrative tax breaks, college endowments amassed $500 billion nationwide. wealth concentrated small group schools, tilting toward private institutions like ivy league highly selective colleges. 11 percent higher-education institutions united states hold 74 percent money, according analysis 2015 congressional research service.“it’s overwhelmingly weighted towards 1 percent,” said dean zerbe, former tax counsel senate finance committee. “most schools elites country.”the house republican tax plan includes 1.4 percent tax investment income private colleges universities endowment assets $250,000 per student. would apply public schools. passed, new tax would affect 70 elite private colleges, though would touch type offshore benefits texan partnership pursued.on monday, 45 education groups declared opposition bill letter kevin brady, texas republican chairman house ways means committee.college university en