link alcohol cancer? it’s nearly scary seems headline friends panic.citing evidence, american society clinical oncology warned even light drinking could increase risk cancer.once again, we’ve told something eat drink going kill us. again, we’re provided opportunity: nuanced discussion risk — communicate — leave us much happier, perhaps healthier.let’s begin fact it’s easy use studies talk cancer. nothing illustrates better classic 2013 study examined research 40 common ingredients selected ordinary cookbook. researchers found 264 different studies touching least one ingredients. conclusion? depending look, find evidence says nearly everything eat associated higher rates cancer lower rates cancer.the gist oncology society announcement reasonable amount evidence finding association cancers (specifically oropharyngeal larynx cancer, esophageal cancer, hepatocellular carcinoma, breast cancer colon cancer) alcohol. acknowledges greatest risks drink heavily, cautions even modest drinking may increase risk cancer. united states, announcement also notes, 3.5 percent cancer deaths attributable alcohol.of course, means 96.5 percent cancer deaths attributable alcohol. eliminate heavy drinking, one endorses healthy association surest, number climbs. also eliminate smoke — smoking believed intensify relationship alcohol cancer — number cancer deaths attributable alcohol approaches 100 percent.let’s stipulate may correlation light moderate drinking cancers. still don’t know relationship causal, let’s accept there’s least association. breast cancer — cancer seems garnering headlines — light drinking associated relative risk 1.04 announcement. relative risk refers percentage change one’s absolute (overall) risk result change behavior. (and 1.04 4 percent change 1.0, represents baseline difference risk experimental group control group.)a 40-year-old woman absolute risk 1.45 percent developing breast cancer next 10 years. announcement would argue she’s light drinker, risk would become 1.51 percent. absolute risk increase 0.06 percent. using what’s known number needed harm, could interpreted 1,667 40-year-old women became light drinkers, one additional person might develop breast cancer. 1,666 would see difference.of course, moderate heavy drinking might increase risks further. absolute risks 40-year-old would go 1.78 percent 1.45 percent moderate drinker, 2.33 percent heavy drinker. numbers still scary.but maybe increase risk much you. that’s fine. you’re one people, though, acknowledge can’t look one cancer vacuum. person get almost cancer.the large meta-analysis upon announcement based looked 23 types cancer respect alcohol consumption. found harmful relationship three light drinking. also found protective relationships — meaning decreased risk cancer — six light drinking.i’m arguing engage light drinking avoid six cancers. i’m merely pointing cherry-picking allows come different conclusions. respect moderate drinking, harmful relationships seven cancers protective relationships three. announcement focused former, latter.a 2013 meta-analysis annals oncology looked cancers found that, all, light drinking protective; moderate drinking effect; heavy drinking detrimental.it’s even cherry-picking focus cancer, though. person get number diseases, fact makes dangers light moderate drinking even muddier.if accept methodology case-control cohort studies, many links alcohol cancer arise, accept results similar studies diseases. instance, cohort study 6,000 people found drank least week better cognitive function middle age didn’t. 2004 systematic review found moderate drinkers lower rates diabetes (up 56 percent lower, although that’s relative risk reduction).randomized controlled trials alcohol (they exist) show light moderate drinking lead reduction risk factors heart disease, diabetes stroke. protective factors may greater negative risk factors (even cancer) might associated light moderate drinking. women die united states heart disease cancer. men.moreover, dire warnings consequences. know far many people throw hands every news story seems “everything” causes cancer. stories rarely acknowledge alternative point view. absolute risks light moderate drinking small, many people derive pleasure occasional cocktail glass wine. it’s perfectly reasonable even risk exists — overall risk debatable — decide quality life gained drink greater potential harms entails.this true many, many foods, alcohol.what this? could make simple changes better understanding risk new proclamation doesn’t send us tizzy:1) consider absolute risks. 30 percent increase risk sounds scary, increase 1 percent 1.3 percent absolute risk not, though things. likewise, concerned 5 percent risk increase 21 percent 20 percent 30 percent increase 1.3 percent 1 percent.2) don’t give much weight observational data. especially true causal data available.3) don’t focus one disease ignoring others. something may harmful regarding one disease beneficial regarding another.4) don’t cherry-pick. is, don’t focus studies, results. review evidence holistic picture possible.5) acknowledge harms, well benefits, recommendations. consider cost joy.these rules may make exciting headlines. may, however, lead happier, perhaps healthier, lives.
unsung role ordinary citizens played great crime decline theories great crime decline swept across nearly every major american city last 25 years focused would-be criminals.their lives changed many ways starting 1990s: strict new policing tactics kept closer watch them. mass incarceration locked growing numbers. crack epidemic ensnared many began recede. even unorthodox theories — around rise abortion, reduction lead spread a.d.h.d. medication — argued larger shifts society altered behavior (and existence) potential criminals.but none explanations paid much attention communities violence plummeted most. new research suggests people working hard, little credit, address problem themselves.local nonprofit groups responded violence cleaning streets, building playgrounds, mentoring children employing young men real effect crime rate. that’s patrick sharkey, sociologist new york university, argues new study forthcoming book. mr. sharkey doesn’t contend community groups alone drove national decline crime, rather impact major missing piece.“this part completely overlooked ignored national debates crime drop,” said. “but think it’s fundamental happened.”between early 1990s 2015, homicide rate america fell half. rates robbery, assault theft tumbled tandem. new york, washington san diego, murders dropped 75 percent. although violence increased last two years cities, including chicago baltimore, even places remain safer 25 years ago. crime continued fall cities, notably new york, shootings record low.this long-term trend fundamentally altered city life. transformed fear-inducing parks subways vibrant public spaces. lured wealthier whites back cities. raised life expectancies black men. even age widening urban inequality, meant daily lives disadvantaged less dangerous generation ago. poor neighborhoods, mr. sharkey found, greatest beneficiaries tectonic change safety.the communities participating another big shift started 1990s: number nonprofits began rise sharply across country, particularly addressing neighborhood youth development.mr. sharkey doctoral students gerard torrats-espinosa delaram takyar used data national center charitable statistics track rise nonprofits 264 cities across 20 years. nonprofits likely form communities gravest problems. also sprang reasons little local crime trends, expansion philanthropic funding. spike nonprofits addressing subjects like arts medical research occurred era.comparing growth kinds nonprofits, researchers believe able identify causal effect community groups: every 10 additional organizations city 100,000 residents, estimate, led 9 percent drop murder rate 6 percent drop violent crime.in criminology field produced eyebrow-raising ideas, one actually surprising. national finding echoes local studies individual programs, like one run pennsylvania horticultural society converts abandoned lots green spaces linked philadelphia reduced gun violence.the research also affirms tenets community policing: neighborhoods vital policing themselves, address complex roots violence ways fall beyond traditional police work.“it’s absolutely consistent would argue probably prevalent theory policing among major cities today,” richard myers, executive director major cities chiefs association, said new research.local organizations also say mr. sharkey’s results validate already witnessed.“any time people’s basic needs met, violence goes — that’s new,” said noreen mcclendon, directs nonprofit concerned citizens south central los angeles.the group, led ms. mcclendon’s mother many years, formed 1980s fight proposed waste incinerator neighborhood. evolved 1990s address many neighborhood’s challenges. group created dozens block clubs care individual streets. cleaned alleys repaired potholes, hired local ex-offenders work. established credit union, sponsored jazz festival developed hundreds units affordable housing.during time major disinvestment cities, severe cuts federal support urban programs, residents neighborhood believed one else coming help. “nobody,” ms. mcclendon said. group done work itself? “there would lot death,” said, “between violence amongst people, violence police brutality, drugs.”many similar groups explicitly think violence prevention. creating playgrounds, enabled parents better monitor children. connecting neighbors, improved capacity residents control streets. forming after-school programs, offered alternatives crime.in east lake neighborhood atlanta, crime rate mid 1990s 18 times national average. drug market neighborhood estimated $35 million business year. hadn’t new building permit issued neighborhood nearly three decades, sign little anyone invested community buy drugs there.then newly formed east lake foundation developed new mixed-income housing replace decaying public housing project. started golf program neighborhood children nearby long-deteriorating golf course. foundation eventually opened charter school, first class seniors 100 percent graduation rate may.“we knew wanted see violence crime go community,” said carol naughton, led foundation years today president national group, purpose built communities, trying teach east lake’s model cities. “but we’ve never crime-prevention program.”today violent crime east lake 90 percent 1995. ms. naughton momentarily perplexed question whether believes groups like gotten enough credit contributing outcome.“we’re part crime-reduction world, public safety world, way we’re part health education housing world,” said. “it never occurred us we’re getting credit, don’t even know world there.”the lesson response, mr. sharkey’s work — effective crime prevention doesn’t necessarily look like stop-and-frisk, hot-spot policing, mass incarceration — particularly relevant today cities rethink policing.“a lot communities despair needed resources,” said robert sampson, sociologist harvard studied chicago neighborhoods damaged violence. “and get? well, mainly got crime control. got increases incarceration.”those tactics may contributed decline crime well. they’ve come costs become clearer time, antagonizing communities disrupting families.mr. sharkey pointing one possible solution less evident downsides. he’s suggesting communities effectively take roles police say strained they’ve increasingly asked perform jobs weren’t trained for, guidance counselors marriage therapists substance-abuse experts.“they taking burden away police probably never there, default kind landed there,” said mr. myers chiefs association, also former longtime police chief himself, michigan, virginia, colorado elsewhere.as mr. sharkey publishes findings, crime rates diverging generation violence fell reliably year year nearly everywhere. it’s clear yet whether great crime decline writes continue. argues it’s time new model violence prevention, one relies heavily kind work community groups quietly aggressive police tactics tough sentencing trump administration advocates.“the model we’ve relied control violence long time broken down,” mr. sharkey said. communities want police step back, pointing people step in. “this gives us model. gives us another set actors play larger role.”
