30 vaquita porpoises left. one died rescue mission. windy afternoon last weekend, cynthia smith boat gulf california, searching one rarest marine mammals world.never vaquita porpoise successfully captured cared humans. dr. smith, veterinarian group known vaquita cpr, knew porpoises — whose black-rimmed eyes dark noses earned moniker “panda sea” — likely disappear without human intervention. scientists estimate fewer 30 vaquitas left wild. last resort.when dr. smith team spotted pair porpoises, managed haul female, hopeful: vaquita calm, vital signs promising. soon moved sea pen began swimming rapidly, abruptly slowed down. time veterinarians released vaquita back wild, late. “she longer breathing,” dr. smith said. “we couldn’t bring back.”in past five years, vaquita population — lives sliver water mexico’s mainland baja california — plummeted 90 percent. humans blame, even hunting vaquitas themselves.the animals, world’s smallest porpoises, get tangled drown nets set illegally catch another endangered species, fish called totoaba. poachers’ bounty organ totoaba called swim bladder, considered delicacy status symbol china sell $50,000 black market. dubbed “aquatic cocaine.”mexico banned totoaba fishing 1993, 2015 — vaquita numbers dwindled 100 — government also banned gill nets, including used catching shrimp kinds fish. gill nets catch totoaba, also trap vaquitas.fishermen still allowed use different type net, intended catching corvina fish, supposed pose threat vaquitas. corvina totoaba fishing seasons overlap, fishermen hide totoaba nets beneath corvina nets boats, said lorenzo rojas-bracho, director vaquita cpr. “you use corvina cover-up, that’s happened,” said.most region’s fishermen, work since ban, poach totoaba swim bladders, fetch $3,000 $10,000 per kilogram, said andrea crosta, director group investigates totoaba trade. equivalent catch shrimp might earn fisherman $200 best.“if you’re water, you’re risking jail time catch shrimp,” said dave bader, spokesman vaquita cpr.after death captured vaquita, scientists agreed shut program. “the evidence today vaquita good candidates protected way,” dr. smith said. “it’s heartbreaking.”the scientists hoped keep animals captivity temporarily, possibly even breed them, gill nets eliminated habitat. wild animal expected experience stress captured, group hoped vaquita could cope handled. (last month, scientists released vaquita calf pulled waters determined young separated mother.)other conservationists critical plan. “i telling going happen, you’re going stress animals,” said paul watson, founder sea shepherd conservation group, also works protect vaquitas. “they elusive, shy; you’re going kill one them.”mr. crosta said admired work biologists, couldn’t possibly solve problem “that starts san felipe ends shop china.” fate vaquita, said, “entirely hands law enforcement.”in past two years, sea shepherd local groups recovered 25,000 yards gill nets gulf, weighing 50 tons. efforts capture vaquitas failed, conservationists say hauling poachers’ nets best bet save species extinction.the mexican government, conservationists say, also needs crack illegal fishing, providing sustainable alternatives community. financial compensation government often never makes hands fishermen, diverted corruption, mr. crosta said.local economies important consideration conservation biology, dr. rojas-bracho said. “you cannot save vaquita, drive fishers extinction.”
