‘it’s black thing’: offensive quip becomes rallying cry brazil são paulo, brazil — black brazilians reappropriated insulting quip prominent television anchorman, using words — “it’s black thing” — draw attention contributions brazilians african ancestry lingering impact racial subjugation brazil.the quip made video recorded last year surfaced week brazil.in video, william waack, anchorman brazil’s largest television network, globo, preparing live shot guest, white house background, covering presidential campaign united states.in response loud honking nearby car, mr. waack said breath, “it’s black thing. doubt,” laughed guest.reaction social media swift indignant video started circulate.by wednesday evening, #écoisadepreto — portuguese “it’s black thing” — one top trending topics twitter brazil.the day, shortly mr. waack scheduled anchor news show, globo announced “removed” mr. waack situation could clarified.“globo viscerally opposed racism forms,” company said statement, adding mr. waack made comments “everything indicates racist nature.”the video leaked former video editor globo, said appalled remarks time afraid could lose job released video public.the video editor, diego rocha pereira, longer works network, said heard comments sat network’s control room.“i rewound video sure, couldn’t believe would said that,” told jovem pan radio station. “i disgusted, recorded cellphone.”mr. waack publicly responded. statement, globo said, “waack affirms doesn’t remember said, given audio clear, offers sincere apologies feel offended.”on social media, remark turned campaign, shining light accomplishments famous black brazilians like 19th-century novelist poet machado de assis, well global leaders, including nelson mandela, sports stars artists.many people written twitter struggles country long history slavery racism. one person wrote: “#it’sablackthing mother, black, single woman, raising 7 children without help white man (my father).”brazil last country americas abolish slavery, 1888. three centuries, four million africans brought forced work fields, mines private homes.today, 50 percent brazilians identify black biracial, many brazilians say racial harmony exist united states.but others say figures point different reality — brazil country life expectancy black men considerably lower white counterparts, people african descent earn 36 percent less nonblack brazilians.in recent years, globo television networks used powerful positions combat racism prominent roles black brazilians soap operas reality tv shows.when brazil’s first black weather broadcaster prime-time news broadcast — maria júlia coutinho, known widely nickname, maju — subjected verbal abuse, colleagues globo promoted #weareallmaju campaign.in case mr. waack, veteran journalist gained respect colleagues years coverage fall berlin wall numerous conflicts middle east, globo said talks would happen next.
