older people play dodgeball, too: ‘we animals’ lot whooping hollering group exuberant students gathered recess time asphalt green upper east side. playing game called “popcorn.”“listen everyone,” yelled one instructors, zack cruz, quiet noise. “we going throw ball air, clap one time, catch it, pass neighbor. everyone ready go? say yes!”one student crouched down. “we this,” said.but student 8; probably 80s. popcorn players day retirement age, older.since mid-1980s, asphalt green specialized creating athletic programs children. one biggest initiatives nonprofit sending coaches new york city schools play active games 28,000 children recess.this year, however, asphalt green trainers decided apply expertise older generations, developing class called skills motion, features adult versions playground games. older people “are different type kid,” said mr. cruz. “you young kids, big kids. want free silly.”over next hour, group mastered game, adding balls, complexity, mix. split teams played volleyball colorful balloons. formed circle holding hands passed around hula hoop without letting go, using bodies. beat rhythm sticks air, dancing favorite songs ’60s ’80s.they also played versions dodgeball, tag fireball, required rolling ball around circle using hands paddles.“when tell friends i’m going 60-plus class, think i’m sitting chair, stretching,” said lois siegel, 79. “but animals. fight balloon ball. feel like kid again.”the program currently tried five locations across city: asphalt green campuses (on upper east side battery park city), carter burden roosevelt island senior center, two union settlements east harlem. right 70 participants. asphalt green hoping make program available thousands next year.instructors say constantly surprised students’ competitiveness enthusiasm moving strenuous creative ways. “earlier go ground, one starting bear crawl,” said samantha frazier, one coaches. “that person didn’t even want bend first, goes.”that’s exactly idea. class created challenge older people move ways preserve strength coordination future. activities deliberately test balance, participants learn readjust bodies keep two feet ground.“if someone throws ball, don’t know going go, react,” said david ludwig, asphalt green’s director community programs.“we want show floor enemy,” said marcy simon, manager senior fitness programs. “you know get floor without hurting yourself.”preventing older people falling, mr. ludwig said, small feat. according new york state department health, annual cost hospitalizations falls around $1.7 billion. top that, 60 percent hospitalizations lead stays nursing homes rehabilitative centers, compounds costs even more.“i’ve never fallen, thank god,” said jennie lorenzana, 74, lives upper east side. “but take class makes feel confident. hour goes fast — fast.”that said, balloon volleyball shouldn’t prevention method people, experts say. “workout classes alone best way prevent falls,” said kathleen cameron, senior director center healthy aging national council aging. “other factors include reviewing medications, making home safe, getting eyes ears checked regularly, talking doctor family.”ms. cameron added it’s soon tell whether asphalt green program, still pilot phase, produce quantifiable results. nonprofit trying measure partnering team nearby hospital special surgery, specializes orthopedics, survey collect data participants throughout program’s 20-week session.participants need scientific data, however, enjoy robust social life. indeed, playground games seem advantage schoolchildren looking make friends 60-plus crowd.ms. siegel learning spanish new friends, teach new word every time sees them. “i see wave say, ‘buenos dias,’” said ms. siegel, runs workout buddies, explained, local places like dollar tree 101st street. “this class opened many doors me.”
