remembering ‘lost battalion,’ 99 years later actor stephen lang knew going threaded way central park. lost, neither world war army unit talking about, unit became known “lost battalion,” 77th division 307th infantry.what lost — lost public consciousness, anyway — awareness lost battalion’s against-all-odds battle 99 years ago. mr. lang working rebuilding awareness, one performance time.the lost battalion — outnumbered, outmaneuvered outguessed — cut american forces along western front. also hit friendly fire stunned german flamethrowers. captain badly wounded leaned rifles crutches continued give orders single surviving machine-gunner.the casualties almost unfathomable: time reinforcements finally arrived, 107 soldiers killed, 190 wounded 63 missing. little third unit, 194 original 554 soldiers, escaped unhurt.the commander awarded medal honor, intrigued mr. lang professional past: early 2000s, adapted oral histories medal honor recipients book “beyond glory.” performed show military installations broadway, among places.mr. lang said began thinking piece world war “because that’s criteria medal began solidify, war didn’t know much about.”rounding corner stepping world war memorial grove park, mr. lang said story lost battalion complicated numbers suggested. maintained, example, lost battalion’s commander never said words made men famous.mr. lang, tony-nominated actor starred james cameron’s film “avatar,” knows adapted story lost battalion “his dark land,” show perform symphony space 7:30 p.m. saturday, anniversary holiday began armistice day marking end world war i. actor james naughton play damon runyon, quintessential new york reporter-turned-foreign correspondent who, mr. lang’s script, asks commander’s memorable line.“i contend given medal honor words never said, got tired denying,” mr. lang said.the words “go hell.” commander charles w. whittlesey, lawyer early 30s sent france september 1917.thirteen months later, 307th ordered break german lines part huge carefully planned american offensive. one account operation reported “this general john j. pershing’s all-out effort show world united states first army could win war christmas.”whittlesey charge harold holzer, director roosevelt house public policy institute hunter college, called unit “unruly polyglot new yorkers chinese, italian, irish jewish extraction, whittlesey championed.” “his dark land” performed roosevelt house wednesday.“the night mustered out, drank brawled street,” said mr. holzer, introduce “his dark land” saturday, “and cohered.”and war over, remembered — first.the memorial grove began single oak 1921, according central park conservancy. mid-1930s, 26 trees planted area. sixteen represented company 307th regiment, lost battalion drawn. trees dedicated soldiers belonged fraternal organization knights pythias.the conservancy said grove vandalized 1960, 11 commemorative plaques trees disappeared. pythians replaced single monument 1961.hurricane sandy damage 2012, pounding eight trees badly taken out. recently, paths infrastructure around memorial — irrigation drainage systems lighting — rebuilt.this setting monday mr. lang described encounter popularized “go hell” remark.the germans sent american soldier captured, private named lowell hollingshead, message offering end carnage whittlesey would surrender. newspapers, mr. lang maintains, supplied rather colorful language “no.”in fact, mr. lang said, whittlesey never replied germans.what whittlesey said considered germans’ message recorded, mr. lang asserted “go hell” sound like him. american artillery fire rained whittlesey’s unit coordinates jumbled, whittlesey sent message included two sentences prolix “go hell” punchy: “our artillery dropping barrage directly us. heaven’s sake stop it.”after war, whittlesey pallbearer dedication new tomb unknown soldier arlington national cemetery armistice day. accounts, whittlesey seemed uncomfortable day. two weeks later, thanksgiving day, boarded ship havana.after din