20 years financial turmoil, columnist’s last shot past 20 years so, business columnist new york times, i’ve front-row seat bull bear markets, scandals, crises management mischief.but leaving times, last shot fair game. seems fitting moment look back what’s changed hasn’t financial world, better worse.in addition string garden-variety banking business scandals, four seismic financial events occurred time columnist: collapse long-term capital management hedge fund 1998, bursting dot-com bubble 2000, accounting scandals enron 2001 worldcom 2002, mother — mortgage debacle — 2008. one brought world economies precipice wiped lehman brothers raft troubled banks.that many episodes financial tumult two decades seem like lot.some turmoil generated positive change. accounting scandals, example, much rarer since enron worldcom shook financial markets. one reason: 2002 federal law, known sarbanes-oxley, requiring top executives attest accuracy companies’ financial statements.“sarbanes-oxley came effect 15 years ago, fewer accounting scandals accountability,” said jack ciesielski, founder r. g. associates publisher analyst’s accounting observer, accounting research service. “those accounting scandals crisis thankful for; got it, law passed, works.”it’s bad mortgage crisis six years later didn’t result heightened accountability.here’s another sign progress: believe not, corporate directors active oversight used be. egregious board practices chummy appointments less common.nell minow corporate governance expert vice chairwoman valueedge advisors, firm guides institutional shareholders reducing risk portfolios. rattling cages governance field since mid-1980s says she’s seen definite improvement boardroom makeup practices.“when started field, o. j. simpson five boards, including audit committee infinity broadcasting,” recalled interview. “and another company, c.e.o.’s father compensation committee. we’ve come long way.”that’s say problems arising sleepy clubby boards eradicated. “exh