venezuelan debt crisis widens, power company default venezuela showed new signs financial unraveling friday, state electricity company declared default.the announcement country’s first bond default came three days government begin talks investors refinance restructure half $120 billion debt.“this first drizzle huge thunderstorm,” said jose l. valera, international energy lawyer houston office mayer brown law firm. “the whole country venezuela bankrupt.”the electricity company, corpoelec, based caracas, unable make $28 million payment $650 million bond. bond originally issued electricidad de caracas nationalized corpoelec subsidiary decade ago.the default announced notice wilmington trust bondholders complained received payment coupon due oct. 10 grace period ended thursday.venezuela state-owned enterprises — including oil company petróleos de venezuela, known pdvsa — missed roughly $350 million interest payments last month. grace period many end next days.“there going many different debtors sovereign different state-owned companies,” mr. valera said, “and going defaulting time.”president nicolás maduro announced last week government would refinance restructure $63 billion bonds, invited investors meet government committee led vice president. uncertain many investors take part, since united states sanctions restrict negotiation purchases new bonds american-regulated financial institutions.monday could decisive day venezuela’s credit crisis.while president maduro’s committee offer restructuring proposals, international swaps derivatives association, panel formed derivatives industry, meet discuss venezuelan debt situation.the panel discuss whether late partial payments $1.2 billion due last week pdvsa constituted “credit event” could prompt bondholders organize seek payment. creditors could pursue legal action confiscate venezuelan assets abroad, oil tankers even refineries owned pdvsa subsidiary citgo.
review: two contrasting views silicon valley’s influence pervasive influence silicon valley economy, culture politics subject worthy close study. two important new books released week offer startlingly different approaches conclusions complex issues. contrasting epigraphs begin works perfectly reflect respective perspectives.noam cohen, former new york times columnist, opens polemic, “the know-it-alls: rise silicon valley political powerhouse social wrecking ball” (new press), quote “the wizard oz.” mr. cohen, “the self-proclaimed geniuses claiming serve mankind” dominate digital economy far dangerous benevolent wizard overwhelming “collateral damage” wrought “these leaders pursue dreams centralizing relationships — personal, economic, political.” antidote clear present danger, “the know-it-alls” seeks “demystify origins harsh market-based values pumped silicon valley, seem irresistible.” mr. cohen’s telling, historic ground zero pernicious ideology fueled undue influence tech elite stanford university.another former new york times columnist, leslie berlin, become project historian silicon valley archives stanford. book, “troublemakers: silicon valley’s coming age” (simon & schuster) opens advertising copy iconic 1997 apple commercial perfectly captures silicon valley’s conception itself. “here’s crazy ones. misfits. rebels. troublemakers,” begins concluding, “because people crazy enough think change world ones do.”to fair, conflict visions less stark seems two authors focused different time periods. “troublemakers” covers “the generational handoff” happened late 1960s early ’80s “as pioneers semiconductor industry passed baton younger up-and-comers.” mr. cohen’s ire primarily targets “who helped nurture world wide web prosperity 1990s turning investing.”one sympathetic benign view technology industry appreciate ms. berlin’s deeply researched dramatic narrative silicon valley’s early years “troublemakers.” tell story, selects seven lesser-known influential figures follow closely throughout period. include first woman take technology company public, first chairman apple, man played critical roles government create internet industry commercialize personal computer. names likely unfamiliar, meticulously told stories permit reader gain nuanced understanding emergence broader technology ecosystem enabled silicon valley thrive.nuance word comes mind reading mr. cohen’s attack silicon valley’s powers be. first two chapters devoted key figures history stanford’s administration computer science department, emphasizing university’s willingness trade academic rigor financial gain institutional sympathy eugenics early 1900s and, recently, extreme libertarianism. underlying themes, mr. cohen’s view, underpin “the stanford model integrating hacker entrepreneur.” model reflected staking william hewlett david packard 1930s, establishing stanford industrial park 1950s obtaining $336 million payout google stock return granting exclusive pagerank license.it unholy alliance hacker entrepreneur values mr. cohen rails balance book. although pauses handful pages speak microsoft — “if know-it-alls’ values represent merger hacker’s radical individualism entrepreneur’s greed, one man considered forefather: bill gates” — believes negative ramifications “only fully flourished widespread adoption world wide web starting late 1990s.” beginning marc andreessen, developed first commercialized web browser, netscape navigator, “the know-it-alls” proceeds attack character every boldfaced name among tech billionaires. found guilty either always promoting insidious tech dogma places constraints ability disrupt status quo financial gain — case idealistic founders google facebook — along way “seduced power money offered venture capitalists.”the history underpins overarching thesis feels selective less rigorous. niels reimers, founder stanford’s office technology licensing one seven key industry figures profiled detail “troublemakers,” even mentioned “the-know-it-alls.” given complex negotiations required secure university approval, seems like significant oversight book whose thesis hinges part stanford’s supposed unthinking commercialism. statements like computer science “still something obscure discipline late 1980s” don’t hold scrutiny. 1990, almost 800 computer science degree programs offered colleges universities, enrolling tens thousands students.although mr. cohen identified legitimately disturbing aspects tech culture, becomes repetitive, tone unnecessarily conspiratorial. also ignores facts contradict assertions. mr. cohen complains “paypal mafia,” former employees “provided cash, counsel contacts.” mr. cohen finds “something jarring group self-styled survival fittest free marketeers committing strategy collective risk mutual support.”when wikipedia founder jimmy wales profiled contrast libertarian fanaticism raw commercialism know-it-alls, inability raise funding used reinforce point: “wales partners rich friends lean tough times.” narrative makes clear, however, problem flawed business model, lack access paypal mafia venture investors. similarly, mr. cohen directly confront irony story wikipedia’s ultimate success made possible free-riding google’s powerful — view morally suspect — search engine.the tech industry earned takedown book documents self-interested justifications number policies clearly public interest. track record matters including cybersecurity, gender equality privacy shameful. brief profiles “the know-it alls,” sprinkled gratuitous ad hominem observations (for example, mr. cohen writes paypal responsible “releasing wild self-satisfied peter thiel, one-man wrecking crew sowing chaos american society day”), get job done.given profound impact lives technology industry apparent flaws current culture, books leave reader wondering go here. “the know-it-alls” suggests “europe provides model” relying extensive regulation but, given absence european tech giants note, seems like throwing baby bath water. although compelling history “troublemakers” provides number tantalizing clues things got track, focus book. ms. berlin whitewash aspects even valley’s early years foreshadow profound cultural issues emerge industry’s middle age, writing, “it takes certain kind audacity think launch company, much less invent industry — audacity often veers arrogance.” doesn’t go way explore implications, either.when founding fairchild semiconductor discussed, william shockley mentioned passing, ms. berlin notes “had yet fully descended paranoia eugenic fervor would later mar reputation.” fact, paranoia abusiveness least already well known and, given qualities recurring contemporary industry themes, would worth examining.similarly, it’s noted key venture capitalist valentine’s success willingness overlook “deviant” behavior, discussion downside letting hacker culture run wild might made sense.silicon valley’s history still written. books important reminders whether ultimately story happy ending function collective willingness closely examine sector’s origins better understand sources innovation destructive aspects culture allowed fester long.
student borrowers, time start repaying loans along holiday cards friends family members, recent college graduates probably receive notices student loan servicers mail coming weeks.most student loans grace periods — spans time graduation repayment must begin — six months. students graduated spring, time start repaying debt.nationally, student debt totaled $1.34 trillion midyear, according federal reserve bank new york. average debt per borrower 2016 ranged low $20,000 utah $36,000 new hampshire, according nonprofit project student debt.spring graduates typically get notices loan servicer — company processes payments manages student’s loans — following november, payments beginning december. (happy holidays!)the letter servicer include details like payment amount, due date send check make payments online.if received sort notice now, best contact loan servicer, said diane cheng, associate research director institute college access success, nonprofit organization. keep servicer apprised whereabouts, said. even received official notice, still responsible repaying loan.if don’t know servicer is, check national student loan data system find company handles loans borrowed federal government. (you probably already federal student aid id, not, need create one log check loans.)loans banks private lenders, rather federal government, tracked federal database. may able find checking credit report. contact financial aid office alma mater, said persis yu, director student loan borrower assistance project national consumer law center.unless tell servicer otherwise, enrolled standard 10-year repayment plan. worried cannot afford payments, federal government programs offering affordable monthly payments. details available department education consumer financial protection bureau.the department education’s tool estimating repayment help compare payments would different options. users contact loan servicer directly, however, confirm eligibility various options, ms. cheng said.recently, questions raised federal government’s public service loan forgiveness program, intended allow people working teaching, nonprofit, social services government jobs loans canceled 10 years. borrowers, particularly joined program soon enacted decade ago, finding loans thought would forgiven might be, complex requirements.but program remains option current borrowers, long correct type jobs, loans payment plans qualify. “certainly reasons cautious,” said adam minsky, lawyer specializing student loans, “but program still much existence.”ms. cheng advises borrowers submit certification form, provided department education, document employed qualified job payments properly credited, remain track debt forgiven.here questions answers repaying student loans:are grace periods loans?one type federal loan, known perkins loan, nine-month grace period. loans, like federal plus loans made parents, grace period. repayment typically starts soon funds distributed.grace periods private loans may vary, six-month grace periods typical, said martha holler, spokeswoman private student loan lender sallie mae. company’s website offers suggestions organizing loan documents help ensure keep payments. one recommendation: create spreadsheet listing loans contact information servicers.what complaint student loan servicer?you file complaint consumer financial protection bureau department education.are discounts available loan payments?typically, knock quarter percentage point — 0.25 percent — monthly payment, federal private loans, agree money automatically debited bank account.
