gilbert rogin, 87, magazine editor writer droll fiction, dies gilbert rogin, enviable run writer droll short fiction new yorker building toward impressive career top editor sports illustrated magazines, died nov. 4 home westport, conn. 87.his death confirmed wife, jacqueline duvoisin, former photographer sports illustrated. specify cause, mr. rogin declining health years.talented idiosyncratic, mr. rogin managing editor sports illustrated five years beginning 1979, stretch magazine still dominant sports journalism espn fledgling.before that, though, seemed might way career fiction writer. new yorker published 30 stories beginning 1963, humorous tales often seemed least somewhat autobiographical, written several well-received books. 1980 roger angell, magazine’s fiction editor, rejected one submissions grounds — mr. rogin later told tale — repeating himself. stopped writing fiction entirely.“maybe knew i’d exhausted fiction vein,” told franz lidz, one former sports illustrated reporters, 2010 interview aarp magazine. “the idea always back mind. whatever reason, roger voiced opinion, literally couldn’t write fiction again. single word.”gilbert leslie rogin born nov. 14, 1929, brooklyn. father, robert, lawyer. mother, former lillian ruderman, actress who, name billie rudell, made several broadway appearances 1920s.mr. rogin grew manhattan graduated columbia college. 1951 began brief stint new yorker office gofer; assignment second day job bring suit clothes funeral home harold ross laid in. mr. ross, magazine’s founding editor, died.in 1955, two years army, mr. rogin joined sports illustrated, time inc. begun year before. job clip articles newspapers wire services filing magazine’s library, began writing almost immediately, soon reporter.he became known elegant phrasing carefully observed profiles figures like boxer floyd patterson basketball star bill russell. 2014, magazine commemorated 60th anniversary republishing 60 best articles, one mr. rogin among them: “12 days mast,” account participating sailing race california hawaii aboard 55-foot yawl. sailing fan, found experience underwhelming.“it numbing, embittering largely useless 12 days,” wrote. “there plot, suspense. progress lacking memorable incident passage hour hand across face clock. proved curving, erratic line shortest distance two points.”when assignment sports illustrated, mr. rogin began writing short fiction. new yorker published first rogin story, “ernest observes,” 1963, came regularly that, right “the hard parts” november 1978. appeared magazines.a story collection, “the fencing master,” came 1965, 1971 mr. rogin published first novel, “what happens next?” poet l. e. sissman, reviewing book new york times, called “a novel first importance.”a second novel, “preparations ascent,” thematically related first, came 1980. 2010 two novels reissued verse chorus press single volume. jay jennings, introduction republication, wrote similarities run much mr. rogin’s funny, understated fiction.“the protagonist,” mr. jennings wrote, “no matter name, (presumably autobiographical) middle-aged, jewish, manhattanite male, magazine writer eclectic intellectual interests eccentric habits.”as mr. rogin’s fiction, whose admirers included john updike, largely forgotten, mr. jennings speculated oversaturation might played part.“he writing apex market protagonists middle-aged, jewish, manhattanite male intellectuals/writers musers,” mr. jennings wrote. “the ur-text genre saul bellow’s ‘herzog’ (1964), cohorts mailer, malamud others variations theme.”it also certainly help mr. rogin abruptly abandoned fiction. story drew discouraging new yorker rejection back 1980, “my masterpieces,” eventually see light print, 2010, lowbrow reader published it. (it appears anthology “the lowbrow reader reader” well.) magazine also arranged mr. rogin reading event housing works bookstore soho.“gil accustomed upper echelon publishing — new yorker whatnot — was, publishing lost masterpiece idiot’s comedy zine,” jay ruttenberg, editor lowbrow reader, joined mr. jennings getting mr. rogin’s novels republished, said email. “but genuinely appreciative efforts visibly delighted attention.”mr. rogin’s shift away fiction coincided rise top editing spot sports illustrated, eccentric style alienated writers — dan jenkins one — embraced others.“he’d make changes touch light could nod appreciatively,” jerry kirshenbaum, writer editor magazine 30 years, wrote email. “you didn’t feel like fingers chopped way editors. gil, like manicure.”yet could also bellowing red-penciled rage, savvy staff members learned mr. rogin man sometimes strange routines disrupted.“between 2 3, everybody silent took nap,” mr. lidz said interview. breakfast always bumble bee tuna eaten can. would often edit bathroom adjacent office. traveled, assistant sure hotel pool suitable mr. rogin swim daily laps — kidney shapes allowed.an oft-told tale: once, road, mr. rogin turned swim find hotel pool drained; frantically swam mile’s worth laps anyway, racing declining water level.mr. rogin married ruth copes 1963. marriage ended divorce. survived wife, relationship 30 years; married 2010.his oddities aside, mr. rogin adept versatile enough that, 1984, time moved — despite reluctance — discover, struggling science magazine, helped stabilize. 1986 national magazine award general excellence. 1987 mr. rogin became corporate editor, no. 3 editing position time inc. empire.in capacity, helped quincy jones found vibe magazine 1993. volatile impatience seemed grow.“he felt guilty shot,” jason mcmanus, editor chief boss, said occasion mr. rogin’s retirement 1993. “i often made unhappy reluctance take summary action perceived outrage; hand, instantly taken gil’s advice, hardly present managing editors would still employed, would i.”
