anned close many 140 stores — 14 percent total — months ahead.“the goal simple,” mr. ellison said. “we wanted flatten organization, streamline decision-making increase agility rapidly changing retail environment.”
power courts messing politics four newly senate-approved federal appellate judges move chambers seven months neil gorsuch joined supreme court, may seem vindicated conservatives swallowed qualms donald trump last year conviction that, whatever flaws, would save judiciary.yet “but courts” defense mr. trump says less courts: namely, importance swollen beyond constitutional recognition. branch government alexander hamilton dismissed “the least dangerous” overshadow every concern mr. trump, branch dangerous supposed be. originalists believe judges help tame judicial overreach credit mr. trump appointments. take notice fact “but courts” argument reveals judiciary outsize importance.conservatives always hold judiciary awe. judge robert bork, whose nomination supreme court senate rejected three decades ago, became martyr cause originalism believed courts’ demotion constitutional scheme inflated role assumed chief justice earl warren. using reasoning, mr. bork also criticized conservative judges earlier generations, like overruled economic reforms progressive era.now, however, constitutional matter, deference judiciary unites broad coalition right left, dispute how, whether, judiciary exercise far-reaching power overrule people’s elected representatives. liberals long argued favor extensive understanding individual rights, especially issues privacy, stance mr. bork’s judicial modesty correction. originalism diverse movement consists opponents supporters mr. trump’s election. many still support deferential judiciary, growing numbers seek control courts promote conservative ends.the “but courts” argument voting mr. trump percolated largely grass-roots quarters, among religious conservatives particular — one would expected hostility mr. trump. deflating power judiciary might help normalize politics help restore primacy considerations like policy character choice public officials.courts removed wide areas jurisdiction public’s authority, corroding ethic measured majority rule james madison described “the vital principle free constitution.” elected officials willing participants eager shed responsibility courts despite fact constitution imbues ample authority exercise themselves. president barack obama used executive authority provide subsidies health care house republicans said affordable care act authorize, retaliate legislatively, madison’s federalist 51 — paper based separation powers branch’s propensity defend turf — would predicted. instead, sued, essentially asking judiciary shelter rather sticking themselves. raised constitutional objections mr. obama’s executive order immigration, representative jim clyburn, democrat south carolina, dismissed disclaiming authority constitution placed hands: “that’s congress decide, that’s courts make decision.”that emphatically framers thought courts. madison wrote allowing unelected judges last word constitutional questions “was never intended, never proper” republic. hamilton emphasized judiciary power enforcement, judgment.but hamilton’s pseudonymous adversary brutus, opponent constitution, understood power judgment republic. observed constitution gave judges final word, without appeal, constitutional questions supreme court, asked crucial question: would officials unaccountable power behave? answer justices supreme court would “independent people, legislature, every power heaven. men placed situation generally soon feel independent heaven itself.”a simple thought experiment illustrates extent brutus right. within power president deliver majority congress, would conservatives set aside core principles executive decorum, morality economic freedom order attain control legislature? victory would transparently hollow would entail ceding principles obtain power whose putative purpose enact principles first place. thomas jefferson understood this. 1792, political adversary contemplating running house representatives, jefferson concerned real damage could done. consequently, jefferson wrote friend madison, “i think nothing better could done make judge.” rival’s name john marshall.what makes judges different today, much “but courts” conservatives willing forgo important principles attain judiciary? obtaining life tenure allies worthwhile bargain conservatives believe courts substantially powerful long run elected branches medium term. that’s true, something constitutionally awry: judges affecting life america elected officials. are, course, reasons thoughtful conservatives supported mr. trump. many swayed “but courts” defense alone despite myriad concerns mr. trump compelling evidence judiciary grown independent heaven itself.
‘shalane flanagan effect’ works shalane flanagan new york city marathon last week, victory athletic achievement. course, it’s remarkable one: she’s first american woman win 40 years, blistering 2 hours 26 minutes.but perhaps flanagan’s bigger accomplishment lies nurturing promoting rising talent around her, rare quality cutthroat world elite sports. every single one training partners — 11 women total — made olympics training her, extraordinary feat. call shalane effect: serve rocket booster careers women work alongside you, catapulting forward yourself.“shalane pioneered new brand ‘team mom’ young up-and-comers, confidence tear others protect place hierarchy,” said lauren fleshman, became professional runner early 2000s, around time flanagan did. “shalane’s legacy role modeling, women every industry would like see of.”here’s worked flanagan burst onto scene. college, promising female distance athletes would generally embark aggressive training broke down. developed staying power required dominate global stage. didn’t much community support them; domestic women’s distance running fractious atrophied. 2000, example, one american woman qualified olympic marathon, training alone anchorage home treadmill.but things changed 2009, flanagan joined jerry schumacher’s fledgling running group portland, ore., called bowerman track club. team’s lone woman, worked create something new: team professional female distance runners would train together push one another striking collective success. coached man surrounded mostly male runners, time flanagan teammates outperformed men national global arenas.instead threatened teammates’ growing accomplishments, flanagan embraced them, brought women, elevating level become formidable group distance athletes nation. national championships, world championships, olympics: became best runners world.one them, emily infeld, joined club portland college, developed one stress fracture another. contemplated quitting 2014. december, flanagan took aside glass wine talk.“i really struggling — cried told ‘i can’t it, body isn’t built this,’ ” recalled infeld. “and totally changed mind-set. told course bad, believed could better. got better, trained together held accountable. it’s completely changed career.”by following august, infeld become one fastest runners world, taking surprise bronze 10,000 meters world championships.this selfless acts mentorship; camaraderie flanagan fostered teammates served well.“i thoroughly enjoy working women,” flanagan told me. “i think makes better athlete person. allows passion toward training racing. achieve great things own, doesn’t feel nearly special.”in fact, arguably made difference securing spot olympics last year.on searing day los angeles united states olympic marathon trials february 2016, flanagan teammate amy cragg broke away pack early race. spent months training together day ran stride-for-stride matching uniforms. toward end race, flanagan’s face turned red began wilt, staggering bit advantage narrowed.cragg slowed urged on, pacing final miles even fetching water flanagan could conserve energy, remarkable demonstration support racecourse. flanagan barely made across finish line, collapsed cragg’s arms. flanagan able make fourth olympic team go become top american finisher olympic marathon rio, sixth place.“we run thousands miles together; worked hard this. every step way, struggling me,” cragg told months race. “we someone like shalane you’re kind dependent her, back would thing.”this year, cragg took bronze medal marathon track field world championships.flanagan’s leadership style doesn’t fit “girl boss” leadership archetypes flourishing pop culture, ivanka trump feminism, shallow claims support women, yields results. (ms. trump’s kind feminism may attract cheers races, win them.) flanagan talk elevating women; elevates them. win.the flanagan kind feminism — ruthless adherence goals — rarely makes interesting stories moment. took flanagan time turned professional, 2004, year win major international race; years tedium drudgery, robotic routine (churning legs 130 miles week). went first vacation seven years marathon training suffering stress fracture spring. it’s fun, it’s relatable.to sure, flanagan’s unapologetic competitiveness universally popular, respected it. flanagan boldly acknowledged work put marathon training unabashed wanting win race. victory new york involved fist-pumping profanity-laced affirmations crossed finish line front millions viewers.we usually see competitive women, particularly athletically excellent women, one two ways: either competing defeat one another, team self. that’s flawed, limiting paradigm. shalane effect dismantles it: extraordinarily competitive, petty; team-oriented, deferential. elevating women actually act self-interest: it’s lonely top bring others along.so, coincidence that, support system spent years building herself, flanagan finally prevailed.
