arden road” old maps, virtually impassable except mountain bike a.t.v.on sunny saturday october, new travis mills foundation center wounded veterans held open house, elegant old grounds full vets families.“look, v.a. best can,” vietnam-era mess sergeant told me, waited line photographs taken mr. mills. “but stays forever, you’ve served. you’re never same. people need places like this, places vets feel like they’re alone.”now, rooms graced celebrities yesteryear like lilian gish ava gardner edna ferber, wounded veterans families place. made possible support donors, including barbara bush foundation, wayfair new balance — charisma mr. mills.i left open house wearing bracelet imprinted mr. mills’s mantra: “never give up, never quit.” later, took bike ride woods along old elizabeth arden road. headed deeper deeper woods, road deteriorated wasn’t much gnarled footpath shoulders mcgaffey mountain.at one particularly difficult hill, got bike began walking it. met mr. mills, hadn’t given much thought fact two arms two legs, one ever tried kill me, millions americans given lives make life possible. thinking now.and then, one side path, saw single grave, surrounded beaten split-rail fence. put bike walked woods look it.“john rogers,” said. sgt. continental line. revolutionary war. 1756-1849. small american flag fluttered stone.i certain alone old elizabeth arden road. there, heart deep maine forest, well-tended grave. someone me, remembered.
