facebook ignoring anti-abortion fake news last year, weeks election, article site called mad world news began circulating around facebook. headline read “before applauding hillary’s abortion remarks, know one fact ignored.”in article, writer says wants expose hillary clinton’s lies late-term abortions. argues baby never needs aborted save mother’s life doesn’t cite sources studies, presents anecdotes opinion fact. midway story, shares illustration calls “partial-birth procedure” — procedure banned united states. it, describes doctor “jams scissors baby’s skull” “the child’s brains sucked out.”“don’t let lies kill another child horrific manner,” says, concluding piece. article engaged least 1.1 million times, making most-shared article abortion facebook last year, according buzzsumo, company tracks social sharing.last week, company’s general counsel appeared congress alongside counterparts twitter google testify company’s role distributing misinformation ahead 2016 presidential election. facebook says it’s taking “fake news” seriously. label “disputed” stories, brought independent fact-checking partners allows users report false articles.it’s clear whether attempts tackle misinformation work; critics called ineffective slow. there’s another problem, too. far, facebook public focused almost solely politics russian interference united states election. haven’t addressed vast amount misinformation unevidenced stories reproductive rights, science health.evidence-based, credible articles abortion reputable news outlets like new york times washington post didn’t make top list “most shared” articles facebook last year, according buzzsumo. articles site lifenews.com did.lifenews, one million followers facebook, one several large anti-abortion sites command hundreds thousands views single post. sites produce vast amounts misinformation; facebook page organization live action, instance, two million facebook followers posts videos claiming there’s correlation abortion breast cancer. stories often generate engagement content produced mainstream news organizations, said sharon kann, program director abortion rights reproductive health media matters, watchdog group. people facebook engage anti-abortion content abortion-rights content “disproportionate rate,” said, which, result company’s algorithms, means people see it.facebook’s current initiatives crack fake news can, theoretically, applicable misinformation issues. however, several human technical barriers prevent misinformation reproductive rights identified, checked removed — already slow — rate misleading stories.first, question what’s considered “fake news” site always black white. facebook says tackling sources fake news eliminating ability “spoof” domains deleting facebook pages linked spam activity. example, year facebook identified deleted 30 pages owned macedonian publishers, used push fake stories united states politics, alarms sounded sites country spreading misinformation 2016 campaign. (facebook says sites may taken terms-of-service violations.) anti-abortion sites different. mimic real publications, publish pieces real events alongside factually incorrect thinly sourced stories, helps blur line what’s considered news blog “fake news.”second, facebook says one key aims tackling fake news remove profit incentive, says “most false news financially motivated.” says hopes making difficult people behind fake news sites buy ads platform detecting deleting spam accounts, says major force behind spread misinformation.however, incentive people write content anti-abortion news sites facebook pages ideological, financial. anti-abortion, anti-science content isn’t written spammers hoping make money, ordinary people driven religious political beliefs. aim isn’t profit ads. it’s convince readers viewpoint: abortion morally wrong, autism caused vaccines climate change isn’t real.finally, public pressure influences facebook directs attention. facebook may focused fake news united states election now, efforts prevent spread misinformation buildup election practically nonexistent. took action intense scrutiny.now facebook fact-checking partners say focus “on worst worst, clear hoaxes spread spammers gain.” simply put, without increased pressure, facebook’s technical efforts human efforts, like fact-checkers’ trawling flagged content, make likely company, months come, seeking “obvious” flags fake news stories misinformation fueled real people financial incentive. us concerned misinformation around reproductive rights need make heard.the irish government says hold referendum next year whether relax country’s strict ban abortion. abortion-rights campaigners expressed concern role misinformation social media platforms like facebook lead-up vote, it’s far clear whether concerns listened to.curbing spread fake news easy task, facebook says cannot “become arbiters truth” fight fake news. least, company address continuing role inadvertently spreading false information issues go beyond united states election russia.
