news shared twitter drive conversation, study finds years, investigating american media’s influence discourse required studying conversations homes, public square office corridors, try understand prompted them.but paper published thursday journal science offers new, albeit unorthodox, method: authors brought media experiment, persuading 30 outlets agree time publication stories researchers could track pieces affected discussion online.what found even handful stories mostly small publications boost twitter traffic topics race climate 63 percent course week, relative typical day’s traffic subject.“journalists, even small papers, appear quite substantial power affect national conversation politics policy,” said gary king, paper’s lead author director institute quantitative social science harvard university.to study media’s influence, researchers persuaded news outlets publish related stories one 11 broad policy topics randomly assigned weeks. studied twitter conversation topic days followed, compared week after.dr. king colleagues, benjamin schneer, florida state university, ariel white, massachusetts institute technology, spent almost five years study, first three years dedicated observing, learning building trust journalists. key getting board, said, limiting team’s involvement part process often arbitrary: timing publication.“in sense, you’re flipping coin already,” said, noting many non-breaking stories, publication timing subject whims editors news cycle.at times, publications retained right bow experiment, shelve stories publish wanted.the study without critics. creative may be, paper overstates conclusion, said kathleen hall jamieson, studies political communication director annenberg public policy center university pennsylvania.“is methodologically ingenious? yes. know whether findings substantively important? based disclosed information,” said.twitter one social media platform social media one venue national conversation takes place. tweets also hardly amount discussion, ms. jamieson said. many people simply share links twitter, offering, best, lines commentary.without seeing content articles tweets, it’s difficult judge study’s findings, said. (while authors provided names outlets participated experiment, withheld articles involved protect reputations publications.)to participated, though, experiment offered chance better understand influence, crucial issue media organizations.“when opportunity actually measure impact new way, really, really excited. core mission,” said jo ellen green kaiser, executive director media consortium, network independent news outlets whose members accounted majority involved study.while outlets researchers worked small, independent publications, truthout times, study included well-known outlets, too, including nation, progressive, ms. magazine yes! magazine, according authors. all, 33 outlets participated final experiment, though dozen participated earlier trial runs, designed differently. authors say publications participated part study.the researchers principally involved two points publication process: beginning end.each experiment began choosing one 11 broad policy areas, food, immigration, reproductive rights jobs, identified already interest news organizations.the researchers asked handful outlets volunteer collaborate, groups two five, stories choosing related topic. example, authors said, technology topic, group might decide write pieces uber drivers feel driverless cars.the researchers chose two-week window study discussion online, asking outlets publish stories either week, chosen random. would compare discussion twitter related topic week pieces ran week not.the stories, typically published tuesday, could come form, straight news, investigations, interviews, opinion pieces, videos podcasts. outlets treated differently researchers said that, far aware, involvement went unnoticed readers. awareness study varied outlet, editors reporters often informed.“we really get whole editorial teams board, often reporters knew, too,” ms. kaiser said.in end, authors conducted 35 experiments study year half beginning october 2014.the authors tried anticipate criticisms, too. many tweets created bots, acknowledged, found bot traffic consistent week, making essentially background noise. researchers also avoided weeks known world events, say planned presidential speech immigration, might influenced results.
