dinosaurs might extinct asteroid struck elsewhere dinosaurs reigned supreme 160 million years. dynasty came cataclysmic close 66 million years ago asteroid crashed yucatán peninsula mexico site known chicxulub crater, paving way mammals — eventually humans — inherit earth.but extraterrestrial impact happened nearly anywhere else, like ocean middle continents, scientists say possible dinosaurs could survived annihilation. 13 percent earth’s surface harbored ingredients necessary turn cosmic collision specific mass extinction event, according study published thursday journal scientific reports.“i think dinosaurs could still alive today,” asteroid landed elsewhere, kunio kaiho, paleontologist tohoku university japan lead author study, said email.other researchers questioned findings.when asteroid, diameter half length manhattan, struck coast mexico, found rich source sulfur hydrocarbons, organic deposits like fossil fuels, according researchers. scorching hot temperatures impact crater would ignited fuel. combustion would spewed soot sulfur stratosphere sufficient quantities blot sun change climate, setting motion collapse entire ecosystems extinction three-quarters species earth.the chicxulub impact spewed extraordinary amount black carbon, soot, rocks, researchers said. turn launched nearly 60 hoover dams worth soot upper atmosphere, cooling earth’s surface much 18 degrees fahrenheit, said.not every place planet amount fossil fuel reserves sulfur trapped beneath surface. locations less hydrocarbons would jetted less soot sky upon impact created smaller cooling effect around globe. dr. kaiho set determine mass extinction hot spots mesozoic real estate market.he created map world looked like 66 million years ago used present day measurements sedimentary rocks organic compounds estimate global distribution hydrocarbons time.dr. kaiho’s co-author naga oshima, senior researcher meteorological research institute japan, created model simulated asteroid impacts ejected varying amounts trapped soot rock. areas highest amounts hydrocarbons released enough soot stratosphere cool climate catastrophic levels.eighty-seven percent earth’s surface, places like present day india, china, amazon africa, would high enough concentrations hydrocarbons seal dinosaurs’ fate. asteroid hit marine coastal areas thriving algae, would included present day siberia, middle east eastern coast north america, bang would devastating dinosaurs life earth chicxulub impact.scientists involved paper criticized underlying research.“the idea location, location, location important impact, think absolutely correct,” said sean p.s. gulick, marine geophysicist university texas austin. questioned authors’ assumptions soot came affected climate.scientists agree planet blanketed soot impact, argue got there. dr. gulick said asteroid impact likely hurled fiery debris sky, rained ignited firestorms around world within hours crash. wildfires, contends, burning fossil fuels impact site, released immense amounts soot stratosphere.dr. gulick said previous work drilling chicxulub crater also showed small amounts hydrocarbons present time impact.natalia artemieva, senior scientist planetary science institute tucson, added soot played smaller role driving global cooling materials following asteroid’s impact.dr. kaiho responded criticism saying previous soot analysis indicated burned higher temperature seen soot forest fires likely came source, said rocks chicxulub asteroid impact site.
