grecian artifact evokes tales ‘iliad’ ‘odyssey’ two years ago, archaeologists excavating ancient grave pylos southwestern greece pulled grime-encrusted object, less inch half long, looked like kind large bead. put aside focus prominent items, like gold rings, also packed rich grave.but later, conservator removed lime accretions bead’s face, turned something quite different: seal stone, gemstone engraved design stamped clay wax.the seal stone’s image, striking depiction one warrior battle two others, carved remarkably fine detail, features barely visible naked eye. image easier appreciate large-scale drawing original.“the detail astonishing, especially given size. aesthetically, it’s masterpiece miniature art,” said john bennet, director british school athens, archaeological institute.“the stunning combat scene seal stone, one greatest masterpieces aegean art, bears comparison drawings michelangelo show metropolitan museum art,” said malcolm h. wiener, expert aegean prehistory trustee emeritus met.the seal stone comes untouched shaft grave near ancient palace pylos. grave discovered may 2015 jack l. davis sharon r. stocker, archaeologists university cincinnati digging pylos 25 years.“it cleaning, process drawing photography, excitement slowly rose gradually came realize unearthed masterpiece,” wrote journal hesperia.the seal stone presents two mysteries. one engraved detail. whether battle scene, strongly evocative homer’s “iliad” “odyssey,” depicts event contributed oral tradition behind works homer.the seal stone’s owner, known griffin warrior mythical animal depicted grave, buried around 1450 b.c. lived critical period minoan civilization crete transferred cities greek mainland.local chieftains, griffin warrior may been, used precious items crete advertise membership greek-speaking elite incipient mycenaean civilization, first mainland europe. descendants, century later, built great palaces pylos, mycenae tiryns, places mentioned homer.dr. davis dr. stocker believ