cool beginnings volcano’s supereruption supervolcano’s underground ocean magma isn’t seething, red-hot molten lava might imagine. instead, it’s likely low enough temperature solid.that’s according new analysis volcanic leftovers ancient california supereruption, shows magma melted shortly volcano erupted. findings, published monday proceedings national academy sciences, might help scientists forecast volcanoes pose threat.the supereruption question occurred 765,000 years ago, carving vast volcanic depression that’s 20 miles long 10 miles wide, known long valley caldera near california’s mammoth mountain. process, ejected giant quantity ash hot gas one nightmarish week, enough leave layer debris spread pacific ocean nebraska.“it would completely wiped everything within 50 kilometers caldera,” said brad singer, geologist university wisconsin madison study’s co-author. “all vegetation biota area would extinguished.”scientists don’t expect long valley erupt again, given enough time another supervolcano likely scar planet. so, nathan andersen, geologist georgia institute technology, analyzed 49 crystals bishop tuff — fossilized ash deposit long valley’s supereruption.these crystals — elements locked within — contain clues supervolcano erupted. take element argon example. hot crystals can’t retain argon, team didn’t expect see eruption. instead, found roughly half crystals contained argon much 16,000 years older eruption.the data — tiffany rivera, geologist westminster college utah involved study, calls “exquisite” — surprising implications.they suggest crystals older argon stored hot magma long eruption. fact, argon retained crystals surrounded magma that’s less 500 degrees celsius. magma, that’s quite chilly — chilly fact, would solid.and yet, scientists estimate supereruption occurred, magma 785 degrees celsius. explain discrepancy, team suspects heat infiltrated system quickly argon didn’t time escape. heat likely awoke cool supervolcano, pushing toward eruption less hundred years — perhaps within decades.that’s far cry lethargic time scales often define field geology. yet, recent research yellowstone supervolcano wyoming taupo supervolcano new zealand also suggested events leading supereruptions occur human time scales.the findings suggest supervolcano wake extremely cold state, raising questions solid ocean magma could melt mobilize rapidly.“the physics works still worked debated,” dr. andersen says. many think injection fresh magma volcano likely trick.and given long valley’s magma sits mere five kilometers surface, event wouldn’t gone unnoticed, dr. gualda says. waters circulating crust would started heat up, generating new hydrothermal features like geysers, hot springs mud pots landscape started boil over. ground, too, would swelled upward supervolcano’s magma reservoir grew.should supervolcanoes play rules long valley, results could help scientists read signals unrest preceding future supereruptions even smaller eruptions.
dinosaurs’ demise, many mammals seized day dinosaurs away, mammals play.that’s basic idea behind “nocturnal bottleneck” hypothesis, concept proposed 1942 suggested mammals could survived dinosaur-dominated world avoiding sharp-toothed beasts day coming night.mammalogists long thought earliest shared ancestor mammals nocturnal, study published monday provides potential date furry creatures stopped cowering shadows started venturing daylight.the researchers found first mammals active day night appeared around 65.8 million years ago, 200,000 years extinction event led demise dinosaurs. likely ancestors even-toed ungulates, like today’s cattle, llamas hippopotamuses, well cetaceans like whales dolphins.“in evolutionary time 200,000 years hardly anything. it’s almost immediately,” said roi maor, doctoral student tel aviv university israel university college london, lead author paper appeared nature ecology & evolution.they also found first mammals clearly diurnal, active daytime, appeared 52.4 million years ago, 13 million years dinosaurs died out. among mammals early monkeys apes, ancestors today’s gorillas, gibbons humans.mr. maor cautioned study showed correlation, causation, nonavian dinosaurs went extinct mammals became daytime creatures. finding adds support 75-year-old hypothesis describing ancestors inherited day dinosaurs disappeared.using computer program, mr. maor colleagues plugged behavioral data 2,415 mammal species noted whether species nocturnal, diurnal, cathemeral (irregularly active day night). analysis also evaluated ancestry information showed closely related species one another.“think atlas. show species alive today one ancestors mapped onto road map,” said. “our algorithm told us whether ancestors diurnal nocturnal.”it showed expected behavioral patterns ancestors going back least 166 million years ago mesozoic, highlighted shift nocturnal daylight activity among mammalian ancestors 66 million years ago, calamity struck planet.their data set represented 91 percent mammal families. 60 percent nocturnal, like vampire bat, fennec fox four-toed hedgehog, 26 percent diurnal like eastern gray squirrel, giraffes humans. rest characterized cathemeral like star-nosed mole, european rabbit muskrat.lars schmitz, evolutionary biologist claremont colleges, california involved study, said excited see large comparative study, study’s finding mammals emerged daylight supports nocturnal bottleneck hypothesis.“this seems support people saying, mammals predominantly nocturnal niche could expand daytime dinosaurs gone,” said.but noted limitation work includes living species extinct ones. without knowing behavior, researchers may missing important clues mammals first carpe diem-ed.
humongous fungus genes made way thousands years ago, two microscopic spores spawned created monster. grew — three feet year — sending dark, gnarly, threadlike organs called rhizomorphs explored subterranean darkness, foraging food. it’s nebulous body, tangled mat beneath oregon soil occupies area size three central parks may weigh much 5,000 african elephants.its scientific name armillaria ostoyae, call humongous fungus. it’s largest known terrestrial organism planet, according united states forest service. it’s also deadly forest pathogen.although none (that know of) big, many others armillaria genus. fungi cause root rot disease plants forests, parks, orchards vineyards across north america, europe asia. sets apart fungi stringy rhizomorphs find weak trees, colonize roots, kill eat them.an international group scientists led hungarian researchers completed first step defeating fungal demogorgons. genetic analysis published monday journal nature ecology evolution, uncovered tactics help armillaria develop unusual rhizomorphs, grow big get good killing host plants.the biologists compared genomes four armillaria species 22 related fungi looked unique special proteins gene families. also compared rhizomorphs fruiting bodies, called honey mushrooms, different stages development.they found armillaria fungi expanded genomes copying certain chunks it, meant additional capacity making new rules behavior. way, fungus genes involved making really good bad. example, team found extra proteins killing cells gobbling glue holds plant cell walls together.they also found special tactics hiding: armillaria reabsorb substances lost soil alert trees presence avoid tree’s full defenses. lets kill trees undetected start leeching nutrients dead stuff competing bacteria fungi arrived. competitors show up, armillaria create chemical environment intolerable them.they also found rhizomorphs fruiting bodies shared genes, suggesting researchers point organs hijacked ancient tool kit making cartoonish fruiting bodies generally call mushrooms. specific genetic traits rhizomorphs — red-sensing photoreceptor pheromones related mating — may help seek victims, researchers speculated.however find hosts, pathogenic armillaria ancient. arrived estimated 21 million years ago stuck around reason.in healthy, natural, diverse forests, fungi absorb carbon kill weakest trees, like gangly, underground forest rangers. monocultures made genetically identical trees, stresses like drought cause trees fall weak simultaneously.“this armillaria wipe entire forests,” said györgy sipos, biologist university sopron hungary led study lászló nagy, hungarian academy sciences.while you’re unlikely spot fungal monster like humongous fungus lurking beneath soil, honey mushrooms sometimes appear surface clumped together around tree trunks. beneath bark, may find indicators infection look like dark shoe strings white paint. try remove stump, there’s much rhizomorphs go deep live long.on brighter side, may get witness foxfire, glow rotting wood results infections.
