iving members giraffid family: modern giraffe, familiar zoos african safaris, okapi, zebra-striped back legs lives rain forests central africa. scientists recently argued modern giraffes fact four distinct species. 30 giraffid species time, ranging indian subcontinent china mediterranean coast, said dr. solounias, also research associate american museum natural history new york.giraffids began appearing around beginning miocene, 23 million years ago, said, probably pakistan india.the greatest diversity found greek island samos, near turkey, said, probably eight nine different species time decennatherium rex roaming spain alongside one two related species.the site fossil found, cerro de los batallones (batallones butte), hour south madrid’s city center, first discovered 1991, dr. ríos said. finds clay-like soil included rich collection carnivores, including big cats bears, well giant tortoises, rhinoceroses giant elephant-like creature, said. “it’s really cool.” giraffe fossils found area site digging since 2007.dr. ríos colleagues used information new fossil find redraw giraffid family tree. new tree puts giraffes okapis relatively far away evolutionarily, dr. grossman said, adding understanding animals relationship. “we’re preserving relics two distinct groups giraffes morphologically different,” said.the new family tree, dr. ríos said, “is first step unravel really come from.”the quality fossils others site suggest many research findings there, said dr. ríos, adding past summer team found complete fossilized rhinoceros.
sea slug eats, prefers turducken sea you’re camping woods, tuck salmon you’ve caught bear appears. it’s waiting eat fish, swoop eat you.this steal bear. price human, it’s bagged human-salmon combo meal.this scenario hypothetical, feeding strategy illustrates not, according study published wednesday biology letters. report, team scientists britain italy termed tactic “kleptopredation” described bears, brilliantly colored sea slug, cratena peregrina, that’s length soda tab commonly found mediterranean.these psychedelic slugs, also called nudibranchs, known feed tentacled marine organisms known hydroids, related corals sea anemones. pop polyps hydroids one might pick flower stalk. based lab experiments, authors new paper suggest slugs prefer eat hydroids ensnared plankton, food item nudibranchs aren’t capable capturing themselves.think like wielding living fishing rod. eating turducken. whichever preferred analogy, kleptopredation — using one prey item obtain another prey item — falls outside ecologists’ traditional classifications feeding behavior. there’s predation, there’s so-called kleptoparasitism (when one animal takes food another animal, like pack hyenas stealing fresh kill lion). kleptopredation something new.patrick krug, nudibranch expert california state university, los angeles involved study, said “steal meal, eat you, too” strategy potentially rewrites ecologists understand food chains. “you usually think predator eating prey item, eating prey item eating,” said.to test whether cratena nudibranchs penchant hydroids freshly eaten, authors lab experiments 25 slugs, presenting four mesh bags. bags held nothing, empty hydroids, hydroids fed brine shrimp brine shrimp only.in 14 25 cases, nudibranchs “went straight bags contained fed hydroids,” said trevor willis, marine ecologist university portsmouth britain lead author study. slugs also ate double number fed polyps compared unfed ones.next, researchers analyzed diet wild nudibranchs measuring isotope called nitrogen-15. animal eats another organism, heavier form nitrogen becomes concentrated tissues prey’s tissues, higher food chain go, nitrogen-15 find.dr. willis colleagues found nitrogen-15 levels nudibranchs lower would expect animals eating hydroids only. suggests slugs might getting significant amount nutrition directly small plankton, contain lower quantities nitrogen-15 hydroids. using statistical models, researchers estimated plankton possibly contribute much, more, slugs’ diets hydroids themselves.as sea slugs prefer hydroids who’ve fill, dr. willis speculates it’s way animals get calories plankton also overeating hydroids, depend shelter addition nourishment. “it seems counterintuitive animal would destroy habitat,” said.but purely conjecture now, dr. willis said, adding research “first step” raises questions answers. one whether animals, like nudibranchs eat coral, perform kleptopredation. added unraveling detailed feeding interactions help scientists understand energy flows ecosystems, dynamics might shift climate change.“once idea what’s going species level, put little stories together look whole communities,” said.
