including sort chemicals leach water pipes themselves, surrounding groundwater contamination. studies shown toxic pollutants like benzene toluene spills contaminated soil permeate certain types plastic pipes age. 2013 review research leaching plastic pipe identified 150 contaminants migrating plastic pipes drinking water.“plastics installed without real understanding they’re drinking water,” said andrew j. whelton, assistant professor civil engineering purdue university, author 2013 study. “we don’t know chemicals we’re exposed to.”sensing opening, iron pipe industry started public relations push own, voicing concerns plastic, wooing president trump accolades infrastructure drive setting war two industries.“iron durable. it’s proven material,” said patrick hogan, president ductile iron pipe research association, industry’s main lobby group. “iron’s ground 100 years.”plastic groups criticized studies, saying focus older generations plastic piping conflate different types plastics. also stress pipes independently tested third-party organization.“it’s new material. it’s safe material. it’s independently tested,” said mr. hollands, executive director uni-bell plastic pipes group.the industry outreach, times, overt.at height flint’s water crisis, chief executive one nation’s largest manufacturers plastic pipes, jm eagle, traveled beleaguered city offered replace city’s lead pipes cost.pipes jm eagle would last 100 years long-lasting safe solution, company’s chief executive, walter wang, told city council last february. “this water crisis, contamination issue,” said, “it’s hurting children making sick.”jm eagle, however, faced recent legal problems. 2013, federal jury california found los angeles-based company defrauded states municipalities decade knowingly selling defective water pipes. places, pvc pipes supposed last 50 years exploded first year, causing injuries flooding.jm eagle declined comment previously said litigation based “scurrilous allegations” disgruntled former employee. formosa plastics, taiwanese industrial conglomerate parent company time, agreed pay $22.5 million settlement municipalities government agencies california.the uncertainty potable water pipes kinds exacerbated lack regulation safety. federal oversight materials processes used manufacture plastic water pipes; instead, water pipes certified tested organization paid industry.that organization, nsf international, displays picture capitol building regulatory resources web page runs hotline questions regulations product safety. yet never received regulatory authority federal government. disclose test results pipes certifies.nsf international called testing robust. “if product meet requirements standard, pass,” said dave purkiss, organization’s general manager water systems.for now, flint fitting city service lines made another material: copper, expected cost $140 million. officials discussed creating pilot area using plastic replace service lines houses several city blocks, according plastics news, though flint spokeswoman, kristin moore, said plastic pipes currently consideration.“when take inherent issue needed rebuild trust citizens water system, felt copper way go,” michael mcdaniel, retired michigan national guard brigadier general put charge replacing flint’s water pipes, said conference year.in burton, next door flint, budget realities made plastics realistic choice.the small city 29,000 saved $2.2 million using plastic replace 1930s-era water system state regulators alerted city critically needed fixes. municipality struggling dwindling tax base, savings huge.“we needed safe water, needed fast. needed replace system, pvc good choice us,” said burton’s mayor, paula zelenko. “i’ve got get best bang buck, bucks hard come days.”
what’s stake bonn climate talks? paris climate agreement 2015 key moment battle climate change: 195 countries vowed help limit rise global temperatures since industrial revolution “well below” 2 degrees celsius (3.6 degrees fahrenheit).but paris deal start long, arduous process. world’s nations still struggling translate lofty promises meaningful cuts greenhouse gas emissions. explains diplomats meeting yet another round climate talks bonn, germany, began nov. 6 continue friday.much attention talks trump administration, vowed withdraw united states paris deal 2020. response, gaggle world leaders, american governors, major corporations advocacy groups make big show insisting global action climate change still trundling forward, without president trump.yet much crucial work bonn happen behind closed doors diplomats try build initial paris agreement, crafting new rules guidelines that, hope, help turn hazy national promises concrete action. here’s watch for.the overarching task ever: figuring limit severe global warming decades ahead.under paris agreement, country submitted voluntary pledge tackle greenhouse gas emissions agreed meet every five years review collective progress prod one another ratchet efforts.but far, pledges proved inadequate. industrialized countries — europe japan united states — aren’t track meet emissions goals. even were, current pledges put world course heat 3 degrees celsius more, outcome far greater risk destabilizing ice sheets greenland antarctica, drastic sea-level rise destructive heat waves droughts. stay well 2 degrees, countries would need cut back fossil-fuel emissions far rapidly they’ve promised far.in 2018, leaders plan assess efforts date discuss action could help lessen odds drastic global warming — goal crafting newer, stronger national pledges 2020. that, need agree formal ground rules exercise. “rule book” focus bonn.one widely recognized problem current paris pledges they’re fairly vague.china promised emissions would peak around 2030, country’s energy data notoriously murky, it’s hard tell much progress it’s actually making. similarly, european union vowed cut emissions 40 percent 1990 levels 2030, offered specifics achieve goal — making hard gauge whether european policymakers could realistically much more.at bonn, negotiators discussing make pledges rigorous transparent, countries readily held accountable actions. means tackling questions like: what’s best way track nations’ progress, see they’re said would do? way tell country’s pledge could made ambitious? specific policies working well aren’t?because paris pledges largely voluntary — world leaders would never agreed deal otherwise — one force governments take additional action. but, idea goes, pledges policies made transparent, world leaders better able pressure help more.the final draft “rule book” due next year, may actually get finished bonn, negotiators hoping make significant progress long list items talks. always, diplomacy tends proceed fitfully.even though trump administration vowed withdraw paris agreement, united states can’t formally exit climate talks 2020. state department sending small team negotiators discuss details pact.the united states china still preside working group transparency, though remains seen much influence american officials wield.the administration also hold event bonn representatives energy companies promote coal, natural gas nuclear power solutions global warming. countries expected view american push promote fossil fuels wary eye.in meantime, coalition pro-paris governors officials plan attend conference tout efforts states, cities businesses making reduce emissions despite trump administration’s stance — highlighting country’s deep divide climate policy.discussions around “rule book” assessing ratcheting pledges could prove contentious. past, instance, united states insisted developing countries held strict monitoring standards wealthy countries, china india pushed bifurcated system.developing countries also argued need financial aid wealthier nations expand clean energy adapt ravages climate change.the government fiji presiding bonn conference, put spotlight issues like “loss damage” — is, whether wealthy nations compensate island nations poorer countries droughts, storms rising sea levels emissions causing. paris agreement broached issue briefly, industrialized nations resisted calls held legally liable role warming planet.some climate advocates hoping relatively low-key conference makes modest progress issues like transparency climate finance. scenario, american officials would play quietly constructive role helping craft rule book ratcheting pledges. nonstate actors, including cities businesses, would continue press forward efforts tackle climate change outside formal united nations process.conversely, it’s entirely possible trump administration’s rejection paris deal could lead countries disengage global efforts address climate change. talks could get bogged traditional rifts richer poorer nations. that, turn, could stall momentum right next big round climate talks 2018 — countries supposed get details what’s needed step climate policies going forward.
