trump ignores climate change. that’s bad disaster planners. hurricane irma swept florida keys september, brought vivid preview damage climate change could inflict region decades ahead.the storm washed two sections highway connecting keys, leaving residents stranded days. ocean levels rising around low-lying islands, however, interruption could end seeming minor: 2030, almost half county’s roads could affected flooding.“we know water isn’t going away,” said rhonda haag, sustainability director monroe county, preparing elevate vulnerable roadways keys. task costly, $7 million per mile road, county may ultimately require outside help.in washington, federal emergency management agency leading recovery efforts could cost taxpayers $50 billion devastating storms hit texas, florida, puerto rico united states virgin islands. time, agency wrestling even harder problem: help communities prepare future flooding disasters could far severe anything seen year.complicating task fact trump administration largely hostile discussions global warming. august, week hurricane harvey made landfall texas, president trump rescinded obama-era executive order urged federal agencies take account climate change sea-level rise rebuilding infrastructure.climate change remains polarizing topic nation’s capital, fema caught middle. recent report government accountability office warned rising sea levels heavier downpours fueled global warming could increase flooding costs coastal communities $23 billion per year midcentury unless start adapting now.“there plenty people want debate vocabulary” around climate change, said roy e. wright, fema’s deputy associate administrator insurance mitigation. “but congress’ instruction us attend future risks reduce costs future disasters. look adaptation dimension, that’s resilience. that’s resilience future events.”as hurricane season unfolded, administration officials began hinting would craft new federal flood standard, though unclear whether would take account climate-change forecasts. and, mr. wright said, fema still moving forward initiatives aimed helping states cities defend future floods. even states led governors reject climate science, like wisconsin florida, taking steps prepare worsening flood risks climate change could bring.but controversy around climate rule illustrates tricky preparing future disasters today’s political landscape, especially since experts argue adapting stronger storms several feet sea level rise could require upfront investments beyond federal government willing consider date.“i don’t think scale need sunk in,” said david w. titley, retired rear admiral former chief oceanographer navy heads climate center pennsylvania state university. “we’re talking elevating structures foot. we’re talking elaborate flood defenses relocation efforts could cost billions — trillions.”most planning floods happens state local level, officials making decisions build homes high elevate buildings floodplains. severe disaster like hurricane strikes, federal government typically steps aid recovery.“communities states often want allow much development possible, reap tax revenue,” said larry larson, director emeritus association state floodplain managers. “but there’s major disaster, federal government bail out.”that, experts say, lead type moral hazard. studies shown one dollar invested pre-disaster mitigation prevent four dollars average losses. cities aren’t paying full price losses, may less incentive take costly difficult measures avoid flooding first place — like restricting development along coasts.under national flood insurance program, fema maps areas country risk flooding requires homeowners zones buy federal insurance polices communities enforce minimum construction standards, like elevating new homes 100-year floodplain, area 1 percent probability flood given year.yet there’s broad consensus flood insurance program inadequate, partly maps often outdated don’t take account future flood risks expanding development climate change, partly minimum standards often proved insufficient face severe floods.because congress unlikely refuse aid desperate citizens major flood, fema often strategically nudge localities taking preventive action.after hurricane sandy battered northeast 2012, fema officials took harder look else agency might encourage stronger flood preparation — particularly climate scientists warning floods expected get worse time.“i discussion president obama said, ‘craig, discussion climate change over, need start thinking adaptation,’” said w. craig fugate, fema administrator 2009 2017. “that’s went back team said: start planning future?”in 2015, white house issued executive order requiring infrastructure projects get federal funding rebuilt two three feet 100-year floodplain, take account best available climate science planning. order opposed homebuilders, said would increase costs. (fema working implement order mr. trump rolled back august.)another obama-era change: order qualify disaster aid, states would consider effects climate change hazard mitigation plans submit fema every five years, detailing risks face floods disasters, well possible steps might take minimize losses.most states aren’t scheduled submit updated plans 2018. wisconsin, state whose governor disavowed climate science, submitted one first mitigation plans december described detail global warming could affect state urged measures prepare things like heavier rainfall events. “climate resilience,” plan noted, “is state national priority.”fema also began folding climate adaptation program allows cities receive discounts flood-insurance premiums take additional steps reduce flood risk. community rating system, cities get credit planning effects rising sea levels. officials florida keys planning take advantage credits map vulnerable roadways.a week mr. trump entered white house, fema also unveiled proposal “public assistance deductible,” states would responsible greater portion cost disaster recovery unless took steps like enacting stricter building codes limit exposure disasters. proposal, yet implemented, may face pushback states homebuilders, environmentalists fiscal conservatives say could lessen moral hazard around flood policy.experts caution fema much own. “they can’t force hands communities,” said laura lightbody, director pew charitable trusts’ flood-prepared communities initiative. “ultimately it’s local leaders take responsibility.”“but,” added, “i think federal government woken fact need start thinking seriously future risk.”since coming office, mr. trump moved quickly repeal obama-era policies focused curbing greenhouse gas emissions causing climate change vowed withdraw united states paris climate accord.but, apart rollback mr. obama’s flood order, trump administration restrained directly targeting measures aimed adapting future disasters. environmental protection agency scrubbed mentions global warming website, fema’s climate adaptation page remains.mr. wright, held fema position since 2013, said agency still pursuing many mitigation efforts begun previous administration, working quadruple investments pre-disaster mitigation 2023. administration officials contemplating new federal flood standard could guide post-disaster rebuilding efforts.asked whether skepticism climate change might impede efforts, mr. wright said, “i never experienced obstacle. say full stop.”mr. fugate, former fema administrator, warier: “the direction administration uncertain, hope they’re focused getting rid anything might suggest climate change problem.”alice c. hill, helped develop obama administration’s climate resilience strategy, different concern: unless administration actively engaged adaptation efforts, less likely programs would expand future.“within administration, it’s easy urgent overcome important,” said. “at point, climate change become urgent, it’s still important category — doesn’t need get done today. unless somebody’s actively pushing agencies act, won’t get done.”for example, 2012, congress created advisory council help fema improve flood insurance program maps. council made dozens recommendations, including ways fema could produce maps accounted climate risks help communities plan future.but task costly, requiring airborne mapping much country, congress hasn’t provided sufficient funds fema implement it. first budget, mr. trump proposed cuts mapping programs.ms. hill said adaptation programs may best chance survival they’re explicitly framed climate measures. “this whole issue become highly politicized,” said. “but longer i’ve worked issue, less care call it. talk fiscal risk. fiscally conservative approach.”that framing may catch on. october, representative mark sanford, republican south carolina, wrote letter 14 lawmakers calling white house reinstate federal flood standard. letter avoided mention climate change, noted flood disasters getting worse time — federal taxpayers hook.“taxpayer dollars spent rebuild repair public infrastructure — sometimes multiple times,” letter said. “it makes sense.”while climate experts praised steps fema taken push localities prepare climate change, argue far needed.“i’m proud work we’ve here” mitigation, mr. wright said. “but looking harvey, irma, maria — puts bright light it. we’ve got long way still go.”in florida keys, scientists project ocean levels may rise 2 7 inches 2030, 9 24 inches 2060.“we probably handle what’s happening next 20 years, look beyond that, that’s different conversation,” ms. haag said. sea-level rise ends high end current projections, keys may need extensive aid state federal governments adapt.dr. titley notes netherlands may spend hundreds billions dollars climate-proof shores. “and coastline,” said, “is size massachusetts connecticut combined. math.”robert s. young, directs program study developed shorelines, asserts federal lawmakers may eventually take drastic steps. 1980s, congress passed coastal barrier resource act, identified barrier islands risk flooding declared federal government would longer send aid areas.“it may time start adding places list,” mr. young said. “we need nation decide whether makes sense federal government hold every shoreline place forever.”a move like would politically explosive. 2012, congress passed bill reduce subsidies federal flood insurance high-risk areas, better reflect hazards involved. protests homeowners, congress partly reversed two years later.“if climate adaptation marathon, we’ve run first 50 yards far,” dr. titley said. “grudgingly.”
